# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: replica-plating
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:replica-plating/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:replica-plating/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:replica-plating/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:replica-plating/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:replica-plating/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:replica-plating/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:replica-plating/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:replica-plating/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:replica-plating/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:replica-plating/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:replica-plating/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:replica-plating/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:replica-plating/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:replica-plating/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:replica-plating/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:replica-plating/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:replica-plating/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:replica-plating/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:replica-plating/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:replica-plating/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:replica-plating/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:replica-plating/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:replica-plating/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:replica-plating/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:replica-plating/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:replica-plating/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:replica-plating/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:replica-plating/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:replica-plating/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:replica-plating/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:replica-plating/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:replica-plating/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:replica-plating/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:replica-plating/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:replica-plating/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:replica-plating/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:replica-plating/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:replica-plating/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:replica-plating/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:replica-plating/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:replica-plating/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:replica-plating/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:replica-plating/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Common side effects include rash, nausea, and diarrhea.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It should not be used in people who are allergic to penicillin.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Serious side effects may include *Clostridioides difficile* colitis or anaphylaxis.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] While usable in those with kidney problems, the dose may need to be decreased.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Its use during pregnancy and breastfeeding appears to be generally safe.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin was discovered in 1958 and came into commercial use in 1961.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The World Health Organization classifies ampicillin as critically important for human medicine.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It is available as a generic medication.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin used to also be used to treat gonorrhea, but there are now too many strains resistant to penicillins.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is used to treat infections by many gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It was the first "broad spectrum" penicillin with activity against gram-positive bacteria, including *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, *Streptococcus pyogenes*, some isolates of *Staphylococcus aureus* (but not penicillin-resistant or methicillin-resistant strains), *Trueperella*, and some *Enterococcus*.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It is one of the few antibiotics that works against multidrug resistant *Enterococcus faecalis* and *E. faecium*.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Activity against gram-negative bacteria includes *Neisseria meningitidis*, some *Haemophilus influenzae*, and some of the Enterobacteriaceae (though most Enterobacteriaceae and *Pseudomonas* are resistant).
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Its spectrum of activity is enhanced by co-administration of sulbactam, a drug that inhibits beta lactamase, an enzyme produced by bacteria to inactivate ampicillin and related antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It is sometimes used in combination with other antibiotics that have different mechanisms of action, like vancomycin, linezolid, daptomycin, and tigecycline.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin can be administered by mouth, an intramuscular injection (shot) or by intravenous infusion.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The oral form, available as capsules or oral suspensions, is not given as an initial treatment for severe infections, but rather as a follow-up to an IM or IV injection.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] For IV and IM injections, ampicillin is kept as a powder that must be reconstituted.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] IV injections must be given slowly, as rapid IV injections can lead to convulsive seizures.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is one of the most used drugs in pregnancy, and has been found to be generally harmless both by the Food and Drug Administration in the U.S.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] (which classified it as category B) and the Therapeutic Goods Administration in Australia (which classified it as category A).
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It is the drug of choice for treating *Listeria monocytogenes* in pregnant women, either alone or combined with an aminoglycoside.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Pregnancy increases the clearance of ampicillin by up to 50%, and a higher dose is thus needed to reach therapeutic levels.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin crosses the placenta and remains in the amniotic fluid at 50–100% of the concentration in maternal plasma; this can lead to high concentrations of ampicillin in the newborn.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] While lactating mothers secrete some ampicillin into their breast milk, the amount is minimal.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] In newborns, ampicillin has a longer half-life and lower plasma protein binding.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The clearance by the kidneys is lower, as kidney function has not fully developed.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is contraindicated in those with a hypersensitivity to penicillins, as they can cause fatal anaphylactic reactions.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Hypersensitivity reactions can include frequent skin rashes and hives, exfoliative dermatitis, erythema multiforme, and a temporary decrease in both red and white blood cells.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is not recommended in people with concurrent mononucleosis, as over 40% of patients develop a skin rash.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is comparatively less toxic than other antibiotics, and side effects are more likely in those who are sensitive to penicillins and those with a history of asthma or allergies.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] In very rare cases, it causes severe side effects such as angioedema, anaphylaxis, and *C. difficile* infection (that can range from mild diarrhea to serious pseudomembranous colitis).
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Serious adverse effects also include seizures and serum sickness.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The most common side effects, experienced by about 10% of users are diarrhea and rash.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Less common side effects can be nausea, vomiting, itching, and blood dyscrasias.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The gastrointestinal effects, such as hairy tongue, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and colitis, are more common with the oral form of penicillin.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Other conditions may develop up to several weeks after treatment.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin overdose can cause behavioral changes, confusion, blackouts, and convulsions, as well as neuromuscular hypersensitivity, electrolyte imbalance, and kidney failure.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin reacts with probenecid and methotrexate to decrease renal excretion.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Large doses of ampicillin can increase the risk of bleeding with concurrent use of warfarin and other oral anticoagulants, possibly by inhibiting platelet aggregation.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin has been said to make oral contraceptives less effective, but this has been disputed.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It can be made less effective by other antibiotic, such as chloramphenicol, erythromycin, cephalosporins, and tetracyclines.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] For example, tetracyclines inhibit protein synthesis in bacteria, reducing the target against which ampicillin acts.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] If given at the same time as aminoglycosides, it can bind to it and inactivate it.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] When administered separately, aminoglycosides and ampicillin can potentiate each other instead.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin causes skin rashes more often when given with allopurinol.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Both the live cholera vaccine and live typhoid vaccine can be made ineffective if given with ampicillin.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is normally used to treat cholera and typhoid fever, lowering the immunological response that the body has to mount.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is in the penicillin group of beta-lactam antibiotics and is part of the aminopenicillin family.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It is roughly equivalent to amoxicillin in terms of activity.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is able to penetrate gram-positive and some gram-negative bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It differs from penicillin G, or benzylpenicillin, only by the presence of an amino group.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] This amino group, present on both ampicillin and amoxicillin, helps these antibiotics pass through the pores of the outer membrane of gram-negative bacteria, such as *Escherichia coli*, *Proteus mirabilis*, *Salmonella enterica*, and *Shigella*.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin acts as an irreversible inhibitor of the enzyme transpeptidase, which is needed by bacteria to make the cell wall.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It inhibits the third and final stage of bacterial cell wall synthesis in binary fission, which ultimately leads to cell lysis; therefore, ampicillin is usually bacteriolytic.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is well-absorbed from the GI tract (though food reduces its absorption), and reaches peak concentrations in one to two hours.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The bioavailability is around 62% for parenteral routes.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Unlike other penicillins, which usually bind 60–90% to plasma proteins, ampicillin binds to only 15–20%.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin is distributed through most tissues, though it is concentrated in the liver and kidneys.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] It can also be found in the cerebrospinal fluid when the meninges become inflamed (such as, for example, meningitis).
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Some ampicillin is metabolized by hydrolyzing the beta-lactam ring to penicilloic acid, though most of it is excreted unchanged.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] In the kidneys, it is filtered out mostly by tubular secretion; some also undergoes glomerular filtration, and the rest is excreted in the feces and bile.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Hetacillin and pivampicillin are ampicillin esters that have been developed to increase bioavailability.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin has been used extensively to treat bacterial infections since 1961.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Until the introduction of ampicillin by the British company Beecham, penicillin therapies had only been effective against gram-positive organisms such as staphylococci and streptococci.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Ampicillin (originally branded as "Penbritin") also demonstrated activity against gram-negative organisms such as *H. influenzae*, coliforms, and *Proteus* spp.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] In the United States, it is available as a generic medication.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Horses are generally not treated with oral ampicillin, as they have low bioavailability of beta-lactams.
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] The half-life in animals is around that same of that in humans (just over an hour).
[src:replica-plating/ampicillin] Oral absorption is less than 50% in cats and dogs, and less than 4% in horses.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] An **antibiotic** is a type of antimicrobial substance which is active against bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] It is the most important type of antibacterial agent for fighting bacterial infections, and antibiotic medications are widely used in the treatment and prevention of such infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] They may either kill or inhibit the growth of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] A limited number of antibiotics also possess antiprotozoal activity.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are not effective against viruses such as the ones which cause the common cold or influenza.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Drugs which inhibit growth of viruses are termed antiviral drugs or antivirals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are also not effective against fungi.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Drugs which inhibit growth of fungi are called antifungal drugs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, both classes have the same effect of killing or preventing the growth of microorganisms, and both are included in antimicrobial chemotherapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] "Antibacterials" include bactericides, bacteriostatics, antibacterial soaps, and chemical disinfectants, whereas antibiotics are an important class of antibacterials used more specifically in medicine and sometimes in livestock feed.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The earliest use of antibiotics was found in northern Sudan, where ancient Sudanese societies as early as 350–550 CE were systematically consuming antibiotics as part of their diet.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Chemical analyses of Nubian skeletons show consistent, high levels of tetracycline, a powerful antibiotic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Researchers believe they were brewing beverages from grain fermented with *Streptomyces*, a bacterium that naturally produces tetracycline.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] This intentional routine use of antibiotics marks a foundational moment in medical history.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In other ancient civilizations, including Egypt, China, Serbia, Greece, and Rome, later evidence shows topical application of moldy bread to treat infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The first person to directly document the use of molds to treat infections was John Parkinson (1567–1650).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics revolutionized medicine in the 20th century.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Synthetic antibiotic chemotherapy as a science and the development of antibacterials began in Germany with Paul Ehrlich in the late 1880s.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Alexander Fleming (1881–1955) discovered modern-day penicillin in 1928, the widespread use of which proved significantly beneficial during wartime.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The first sulfonamide and the first systemically active antibacterial drug, Prontosil, was developed by a research team led by Gerhard Domagk in 1932 or 1933 at the Bayer Laboratories of the IG Farben conglomerate in Germany.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, the effectiveness and easy access to antibiotics have also led to their overuse and some bacteria have evolved resistance to them.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR), a naturally occurring process, is primarily driven by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people around the world do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The World Health Organization has classified AMR as a widespread "serious threat [that] is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Each year, nearly 5 million deaths are associated with AMR globally.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Global deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million in 2019.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The term 'antibiosis', meaning "against life", was introduced by the French bacteriologist Jean Paul Vuillemin as a descriptive name of the phenomenon exhibited by these early antibacterial drugs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiosis was first described in 1877 in bacteria when Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch observed that an airborne bacillus could inhibit the growth of *Bacillus anthracis*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] These drugs were later renamed antibiotics by Selman Waksman, an American microbiologist, in 1947.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The term *antibiotic* was first used in 1942 by Selman Waksman and his collaborators in journal articles to describe any substance produced by a microorganism that is antagonistic to the growth of other microorganisms in high dilution.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] This definition excluded substances that kill bacteria but that are not produced by microorganisms (such as gastric juices and hydrogen peroxide).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] It also excluded synthetic antibacterial compounds such as the sulfonamides.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In current usage, the term "antibiotic" is applied to any medication that kills bacteria or inhibits their growth, regardless of whether that medication is produced by a microorganism or not.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The term "antibiotic" derives from *anti* + βιωτικός (*biōtikos*), "fit for life, lively", which comes from βίωσις (*biōsis*), "way of life", and that from βίος (*bios*), "life".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The term "antibacterial" derives from Greek ἀντί (*anti*), "against" + βακτήριον (*baktērion*), diminutive of βακτηρία (*baktēria*), "staff, cane", because the first bacteria to be discovered were rod-shaped.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat or prevent bacterial infections, and sometimes protozoan infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] (Metronidazole is effective against a number of parasitic diseases).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] When an infection is suspected of being responsible for an illness but the responsible pathogen has not been identified, an empiric therapy is adopted.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] This involves the administration of a broad-spectrum antibiotic based on the signs and symptoms presented and is initiated pending laboratory results that can take several days.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] When the responsible pathogenic microorganism is already known or has been identified, definitive therapy can be started.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] This will usually involve the use of a narrow-spectrum antibiotic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The choice of antibiotic given will also be based on its cost.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Identification is critically important as it can reduce the cost and toxicity of the antibiotic therapy and also reduce the possibility of the emergence of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] To avoid surgery, antibiotics may be given for non-complicated acute appendicitis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics may be given as a preventive measure and this is usually limited to at-risk populations such as those with a weakened immune system (particularly in HIV cases to prevent pneumonia), those taking immunosuppressive drugs, cancer patients, and those having surgery.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Their use in surgical procedures is to help prevent infection of incisions.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] They have an important role in dental antibiotic prophylaxis where their use may prevent bacteremia and consequent infective endocarditis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are also used to prevent infection in cases of neutropenia particularly cancer-related.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The use of antibiotics for secondary prevention of coronary heart disease is not supported by current scientific evidence, and may actually increase cardiovascular mortality, all-cause mortality and the occurrence of stroke.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] There are many different routes of administration for antibiotic treatment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In more severe cases, particularly deep-seated systemic infections, antibiotics can be given intravenously or by injection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Where the site of infection is easily accessed, antibiotics may be given topically in the form of eye drops onto the conjunctiva for conjunctivitis or ear drops for ear infections and acute cases of swimmer's ear.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Topical use is also one of the treatment options for some skin conditions including acne and cellulitis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Advantages of topical application include achieving high and sustained concentration of antibiotic at the site of infection; reducing the potential for systemic absorption and toxicity, and total volumes of antibiotic required are reduced, thereby also reducing the risk of antibiotic misuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Topical antibiotics applied over certain types of surgical wounds have been reported to reduce the risk of surgical site infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, there are certain general causes for concern with topical administration of antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Some systemic absorption of the antibiotic may occur; the quantity of antibiotic applied is difficult to accurately dose, and there is also the possibility of local hypersensitivity reactions or contact dermatitis occurring.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] It is recommended to administer antibiotics as soon as possible, especially in life-threatening infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Many emergency departments stock antibiotics for this purpose.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotic consumption varies widely between countries.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The WHO report on surveillance of antibiotic consumption published in 2018 analysed 2015 data from 65 countries.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] As measured in defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Mongolia had the highest consumption with a rate of 64.4.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Amoxicillin and amoxicillin/clavulanic acid were the most frequently consumed.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are screened for any negative effects before their approval for clinical use, and are usually considered safe and well tolerated.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, some antibiotics have been associated with a wide extent of adverse side effects ranging from mild to very severe depending on the type of antibiotic used, the microbes targeted, and the individual patient.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Side effects may reflect the pharmacological or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or may involve hypersensitivity or allergic reactions.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Common side effects of oral antibiotics include diarrhea, resulting from disruption of the species composition in the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as *Clostridioides difficile*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Taking probiotics during the course of antibiotic treatment can help prevent antibiotic-associated diarrhea.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibacterials can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus *Candida* in the vulvo-vaginal area.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Additional side effects can result from interaction with other drugs, such as the possibility of tendon damage from the administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Some antibiotics may also damage the mitochondrion, a bacteria-derived organelle found in eukaryotic, including human, cells.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Mitochondrial damage causes oxidative stress in cells and has been suggested as a mechanism for side effects from fluoroquinolones.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics can also damage the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] It is also known to affect chloroplasts.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] There are few well-controlled studies on whether antibiotic use increases the risk of oral contraceptive failure.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The majority of studies indicate antibiotics do not interfere with birth control pills, such as clinical studies that suggest the failure rate of contraceptive pills caused by antibiotics is very low (about 1%).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Situations that may increase the risk of oral contraceptive failure include non-compliance (missing taking the pill), vomiting, or diarrhea.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Gastrointestinal disorders or interpatient variability in oral contraceptive absorption affecting ethinylestradiol serum levels in the blood.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Women with menstrual irregularities may be at higher risk of failure and should be advised to use backup contraception during antibiotic treatment and for one week after its completion.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] If patient-specific risk factors for reduced oral contraceptive efficacy are suspected, backup contraception is recommended.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In cases where antibiotics have been suggested to affect the efficiency of birth control pills, such as for the broad-spectrum antibiotic rifampicin, these cases may be due to an increase in the activities of hepatic liver enzymes' causing increased breakdown of the pill's active ingredients.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Effects on the intestinal flora, which might result in reduced absorption of estrogens in the colon, have also been suggested, but such suggestions have been inconclusive and controversial.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Clinicians have recommended that extra contraceptive measures be applied during therapies using antibiotics that are suspected to interact with oral contraceptives.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] More studies on the possible interactions between antibiotics and birth control pills (oral contraceptives) are required as well as careful assessment of patient-specific risk factors for potential oral contractive pill failure prior to dismissing the need for backup contraception.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Interactions between alcohol and certain antibiotics may occur and may cause side effects and decreased effectiveness of antibiotic therapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] While moderate alcohol consumption is unlikely to interfere with many common antibiotics, there are specific types of antibiotics with which alcohol consumption may cause serious side effects.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Therefore, potential risks of side effects and effectiveness depend on the type of antibiotic administered.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics such as metronidazole, tinidazole, cephamandole, latamoxef, cefoperazone, cefmenoxime, and furazolidone, cause a disulfiram-like chemical reaction with alcohol by inhibiting its breakdown by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, which may result in vomiting, nausea, and shortness of breath.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In addition, the efficacy of doxycycline and erythromycin succinate may be reduced by alcohol consumption.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Other effects of alcohol on antibiotic activity include altered activity of the liver enzymes that break down the antibiotic compound.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The successful outcome of antimicrobial therapy with antibacterial compounds depends on several factors.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] These include host defense mechanisms, the location of infection, and the pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic properties of the antibacterial.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The bactericidal activity of antibacterials may depend on the bacterial growth phase, and it often requires ongoing metabolic activity and division of bacterial cells.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] These findings are based on laboratory studies, and in clinical settings have also been shown to eliminate bacterial infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Since the activity of antibacterials depends frequently on its concentration, *in vitro* characterization of antibacterial activity commonly includes the determination of the minimum inhibitory concentration and minimum bactericidal concentration of an antibacterial.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] To predict clinical outcome, the antimicrobial activity of an antibacterial is usually combined with its pharmacokinetic profile, and several pharmacological parameters are used as markers of drug efficacy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In important infectious diseases, including tuberculosis, combination therapy (i.e., the concurrent application of two or more antibiotics) has been used to delay or prevent the emergence of resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In acute bacterial infections, antibiotics as part of combination therapy are prescribed for their synergistic effects to improve treatment outcome as the combined effect of both antibiotics is better than their individual effect.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Fosfomycin has the highest number of synergistic combinations among antibiotics and is almost always used as a partner drug.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Combination therapy also broadens the antimicrobial spectrum, ensuring that at least one of the antibiotics in the regimen is effective against the pathogen, which is especially important when the causative agent is unknown.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* infections may be treated with a combination therapy of fusidic acid and rifampicin.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics used in combination may also be antagonistic and the combined effects of the two antibiotics may be less than if one of the antibiotics was given as a monotherapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For example, chloramphenicol and tetracyclines are antagonists to penicillins.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, this can vary depending on the species of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In general, combinations of a bacteriostatic antibiotic and bactericidal antibiotic are antagonistic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In addition to combining one antibiotic with another, antibiotics are sometimes co-administered with resistance-modifying agents.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For example, β-lactam antibiotics may be used in combination with β-lactamase inhibitors, such as clavulanic acid or sulbactam, when a patient is infected with a β-lactamase-producing strain of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are commonly classified based on their mechanism of action, chemical structure, or spectrum of activity.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Most target bacterial functions or growth processes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Those that target the bacterial cell wall (penicillins and cephalosporins) or the cell membrane (polymyxins), or interfere with essential bacterial enzymes (rifamycins, lipiarmycins, quinolones, and sulfonamides) have bactericidal activities, killing the bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Protein synthesis inhibitors (macrolides, lincosamides, and tetracyclines) are usually bacteriostatic, inhibiting further growth (with the exception of bactericidal aminoglycosides).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Further categorization is based on their target specificity.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] "Narrow-spectrum" antibiotics target specific types of bacteria, such as gram-negative or gram-positive, whereas broad-spectrum antibiotics affect a wide range of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] With advances in medicinal chemistry, most modern antibacterials are semisynthetic modifications of various natural compounds.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] These include, for example, the beta-lactam antibiotics, which include the penicillins (produced by fungi in the genus *Penicillium*), the cephalosporins, and the carbapenems.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Compounds that are still isolated from living organisms are the aminoglycosides, whereas other antibacterials—for example, the sulfonamides, the quinolones, and the oxazolidinones—are produced solely by chemical synthesis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Many antibacterial compounds are relatively small molecules with a molecular weight of less than 1000 daltons.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Since the first pioneering efforts of Howard Florey and Chain in 1939, the importance of antibiotics, including antibacterials, to medicine has led to intense research into producing antibacterials at large scales.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Following screening of antibacterials against a wide range of bacteria, production of the active compounds is carried out using fermentation, usually in strongly aerobic conditions.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR or AR) is a naturally occurring process.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] AMR is driven largely by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria is a common phenomenon mainly caused by the overuse/misuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] It represents a threat to health globally.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Emergence of resistance often reflects evolutionary processes that take place during antibiotic therapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The antibiotic treatment may select for bacterial strains with physiologically or genetically enhanced capacity to survive high doses of antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Under certain conditions, it may result in preferential growth of resistant bacteria, while growth of susceptible bacteria is inhibited by the drug.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For example, antibacterial selection for strains having previously acquired antibacterial-resistance genes was demonstrated in 1943 by the Luria–Delbrück experiment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics such as penicillin and erythromycin, which used to have a high efficacy against many bacterial species and strains, have become less effective, due to the increased resistance of many bacterial strains.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Resistance may take the form of biodegradation of pharmaceuticals, such as sulfamethazine-degrading soil bacteria introduced to sulfamethazine through medicated pig feces.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The survival of bacteria often results from an inheritable resistance, but the growth of resistance to antibacterials also occurs through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Horizontal transfer is more likely to happen in locations of frequent antibiotic use.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibacterial resistance may impose a biological cost, thereby reducing fitness of resistant strains, which can limit the spread of antibacterial-resistant bacteria, for example, in the absence of antibacterial compounds.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Additional mutations, however, may compensate for this fitness cost and can aid the survival of these bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Paleontological data show that both antibiotics and antibiotic resistance are ancient compounds and mechanisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Useful antibiotic targets are those for which mutations negatively impact bacterial reproduction or viability.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Several molecular mechanisms of antibacterial resistance exist.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Intrinsic antibacterial resistance may be part of the genetic makeup of bacterial strains.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For example, an antibiotic target may be absent from the bacterial genome.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Acquired resistance results from a mutation in the bacterial chromosome or the acquisition of extra-chromosomal DNA.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibacterial-producing bacteria have evolved resistance mechanisms that have been shown to be similar to, and may have been transferred to, antibacterial-resistant strains.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The spread of antibacterial resistance often occurs through vertical transmission of mutations during growth and by genetic recombination of DNA by horizontal genetic exchange.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For instance, antibacterial resistance genes can be exchanged between different bacterial strains or species via plasmids that carry these resistance genes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Plasmids that carry several different resistance genes can confer resistance to multiple antibacterials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Cross-resistance to several antibacterials may also occur when a resistance mechanism encoded by a single gene conveys resistance to more than one antibacterial compound.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibacterial-resistant strains and species, sometimes referred to as "superbugs", now contribute to the emergence of diseases that were, for a while, well controlled.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For example, emergent bacterial strains causing tuberculosis that are resistant to previously effective antibacterial treatments pose many therapeutic challenges.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Every year, nearly half a million new cases of multidrug-resistant tuberculosis (MDR-TB) are estimated to occur worldwide.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For example, NDM-1 is a newly identified enzyme conveying bacterial resistance to a broad range of beta-lactam antibacterials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In recent years, even anaerobic bacteria, historically considered less concerning in terms of resistance, have demonstrated high rates of antibiotic resistance, particularly *Bacteroides*, for which resistance rates to penicillin have been reported to exceed 90%.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Per *The ICU Book*, "The first rule of antibiotics is to try not to use them, and the second rule is try not to use too many of them." Inappropriate antibiotic treatment and overuse of antibiotics have contributed to the emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, potential harm from antibiotics extends beyond selection of antimicrobial resistance and their overuse is associated with adverse effects for patients themselves, seen most clearly in critically ill patients in Intensive care units.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Self-prescribing of antibiotics is an example of misuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Many antibiotics are frequently prescribed to treat symptoms or diseases that do not respond to antibiotics or that are likely to resolve without treatment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Also, incorrect or suboptimal antibiotics are prescribed for certain bacterial infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The overuse of antibiotics, like penicillin and erythromycin, has been associated with emerging antibiotic resistance since the 1950s.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Widespread usage of antibiotics in hospitals has also been associated with increases in bacterial strains and species that no longer respond to treatment with the most common antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Common forms of antibiotic misuse include excessive use of prophylactic antibiotics in travelers and failure of medical professionals to prescribe the correct dosage of antibiotics on the basis of the patient's weight and history of prior use.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Other forms of misuse include failure to take the entire prescribed course of the antibiotic, incorrect dosage and administration, or failure to rest for sufficient recovery.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Inappropriate antibiotic treatment, for example, is their prescription to treat viral infections such as the common cold.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] One study on respiratory tract infections found "physicians were more likely to prescribe antibiotics to patients who appeared to expect them".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Multifactorial interventions aimed at both physicians and patients can reduce inappropriate prescription of antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The lack of rapid point of care diagnostic tests, particularly in resource-limited settings is considered one of the drivers of antibiotic misuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Several organizations concerned with antimicrobial resistance are lobbying to eliminate the unnecessary use of antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The issues of misuse and overuse of antibiotics have been addressed by the formation of the US Interagency Task Force on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] This task force aims to actively address antimicrobial resistance, and is coordinated by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), and the National Institutes of Health, as well as other US agencies.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] A non-governmental organization campaign group is *Keep Antibiotics Working*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In France, an "Antibiotics are not automatic" government campaign started in 2002 and led to a marked reduction of unnecessary antibiotic prescriptions, especially in children.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The emergence of antibiotic resistance has prompted restrictions on their use in the UK in 1970 (Swann report 1969), and the European Union has banned the use of antibiotics as growth-promotional agents since 2003.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Moreover, several organizations (including the World Health Organization, the National Academy of Sciences, and the U.S.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Food and Drug Administration) have advocated restricting the amount of antibiotic use in food animal production.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] 2562) aimed at phasing out nontherapeutic use of antibiotics in US food animals were proposed, but have not passed.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] These bills were endorsed by public health and medical organizations, including the American Holistic Nurses' Association, the American Medical Association, and the American Public Health Association.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Despite pledges by food companies and restaurants to reduce or eliminate meat that comes from animals treated with antibiotics, the purchase of antibiotics for use on farm animals has been increasing every year.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] There has been extensive use of antibiotics in animal husbandry.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In the United States, the question of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains due to use of antibiotics in livestock was raised by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 1977.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In March 2012, the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York, ruling in an action brought by the Natural Resources Defense Council and others, ordered the FDA to revoke approvals for the use of antibiotics in livestock, which violated FDA regulations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Studies have shown that common misconceptions about the effectiveness and necessity of antibiotics to treat common mild illnesses contribute to their overuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Other forms of antibiotic-associated harm include anaphylaxis, drug toxicity most notably kidney and liver damage, and super-infections with resistant organisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Antibiotics are also known to affect mitochondrial function, and this may contribute to the bioenergetic failure of immune cells seen in sepsis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] They also alter the microbiome of the gut, lungs, and skin, which may be associated with adverse effects such as Clostridioides difficile associated diarrhoea.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Whilst antibiotics can clearly be lifesaving in patients with bacterial infections, their overuse, especially in patients where infections are hard to diagnose, can lead to harm via multiple mechanisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Before the early 20th century, treatments for infections were based primarily on medicinal folklore.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Mixtures with antimicrobial properties used in the treatment of infections were described over 2,000 years ago.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Many ancient cultures, including the ancient Egyptians and ancient Greeks, used specially selected mold and plant materials to treat infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Nubian mummies studied in the 1990s were found to contain significant levels of tetracycline.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The beer brewed at that time was conjectured to have been the source.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The use of antibiotics in modern medicine began with the discovery of synthetic antibiotics derived from dyes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Various essential oils have been shown to have anti-microbial properties.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Along with this, the plants from which these oils have been derived can be used as niche anti-microbial agents.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Ehrlich noted certain dyes would colour human, animal, or bacterial cells, whereas others did not.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] He then proposed that it might be possible to create chemicals that would act as a selective drug that would bind to and kill bacteria without harming the human host.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] After screening hundreds of dyes against various organisms, in 1907, he discovered a medicinally useful drug, the first synthetic antibacterial organoarsenic compound salvarsan, now called arsphenamine.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] This heralded the era of antibacterial treatment that was begun with the discovery of a series of arsenic-derived synthetic antibiotics by both Alfred Bertheim and Ehrlich in 1907.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Ehrlich and Bertheim had experimented with various chemicals derived from dyes to treat trypanosomiasis in mice and spirochaeta infection in rabbits.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] While their early compounds were too toxic, Ehrlich and Sahachiro Hata, a Japanese bacteriologist working with Ehrlich in the quest for a drug to treat syphilis, achieved success with the 606th compound in their series of experiments.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In 1910, Ehrlich and Hata announced their discovery, which they called drug "606", at the Congress for Internal Medicine at Wiesbaden.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The Hoechst company began to market the compound toward the end of 1910 under the name Salvarsan, now known as arsphenamine.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The drug was used to treat syphilis in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In 1908, Ehrlich received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his contributions to immunology.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Hata was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1911 and for the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1912 and 1913.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The first sulfonamide and the first systemically active antibacterial drug, Prontosil, was developed by a research team led by Gerhard Domagk in 1932 or 1933 at the Bayer Laboratories of the IG Farben conglomerate in Germany, for which Domagk received the 1939 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Sulfanilamide, the active drug of Prontosil, was not patentable as it had already been in use in the dye industry for some years.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Prontosil had a relatively broad effect against Gram-positive cocci, but not against enterobacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Research was stimulated apace by its success.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The discovery and development of this sulfonamide drug opened the era of antibacterials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Observations about the growth of some microorganisms inhibiting the growth of other microorganisms have been reported since the late 19th century.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] These observations of antibiosis between microorganisms led to the discovery of natural antibacterials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Louis Pasteur observed, "if we could intervene in the antagonism observed between some bacteria, it would offer perhaps the greatest hopes for therapeutics".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In 1874, physician Sir William Roberts noted that cultures of the mould *Penicillium glaucum* that is used in the making of some types of blue cheese did not display bacterial contamination.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In 1895, Vincenzo Tiberio, an Italian physician, published a paper on the antibacterial power of some extracts of mold.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In his thesis, Duchesne proposed that bacteria and moulds engage in a perpetual battle for survival.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Duchesne observed that *E. coli* was eliminated by *Penicillium glaucum* when grown in the same culture.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] He also observed that when he inoculated laboratory animals with lethal doses of typhoid bacilli together with *Penicillium glaucum*, the animals did not contract typhoid.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Duchesne's army service after getting his degree prevented him from doing any further research.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Duchesne died of tuberculosis, a disease now treated by antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In 1928, Sir Alexander Fleming postulated the existence of penicillin, a molecule produced by certain moulds that kills or stops the growth of certain kinds of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Fleming was working on a culture of disease-causing bacteria when he noticed the spores of a green mold, *Penicillium rubens*, in one of his culture plates.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] He observed that the presence of the mould killed or prevented the growth of the bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Fleming postulated that the mould must secrete an antibacterial substance, which he named penicillin in 1928.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Fleming believed that its antibacterial properties could be exploited for chemotherapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] He initially characterised some of its biological properties and attempted to use a crude preparation to treat some infections, but he was unable to pursue its further development without the aid of trained chemists.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Ernst Chain, Howard Florey, and Edward Abraham succeeded in purifying the first penicillin, penicillin G, in 1942, but it did not become widely available outside the Allied military before 1945.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Later, Norman Heatley developed the back extraction technique for efficiently purifying penicillin in bulk.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] The chemical structure of penicillin was first proposed by Abraham in 1942 and then later confirmed by Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin in 1945.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Purified penicillin displayed potent antibacterial activity against a wide range of bacteria and had low toxicity in humans.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Furthermore, its activity was not inhibited by biological constituents such as pus, unlike the synthetic sulfonamides.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] (see below) The development of penicillin led to renewed interest in the search for antibiotic compounds with similar efficacy and safety.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] For their successful development of penicillin, which Fleming had accidentally discovered but could not develop himself, as a therapeutic drug, Chain and Florey shared the 1945 Nobel Prize in Medicine with Fleming.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Florey credited René Dubos with pioneering the approach of deliberately and systematically searching for antibacterial compounds, which had led to the discovery of gramicidin and had revived Florey's research in penicillin.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] In 1939, coinciding with the start of World War II, Dubos had reported the discovery of the first naturally derived antibiotic, tyrothricin, a compound of 20% gramicidin and 80% tyrocidine, from *Bacillus brevis*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] It was one of the first commercially manufactured antibiotics and was very effective in treating wounds and ulcers during World War II.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Gramicidin, however, could not be used systemically because of toxicity.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Tyrocidine also proved too toxic for systemic usage.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] Research results obtained during that period were not shared between the Axis and the Allied powers during World War II and limited access during the Cold War.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] During the mid-20th century, the number of new antibiotic substances introduced for medical use increased significantly.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] From 1935 to 1968, 12 new classes were launched.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p01] However, the number of new classes dropped markedly, with only two new classes introduced between 1969 and 2003.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Both the WHO and the Infectious Disease Society of America report that the weak antibiotic pipeline does not match bacteria's increasing ability to develop resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The Infectious Disease Society of America report noted that the number of new antibiotics approved for marketing per year had been declining and identified seven antibiotics against the Gram-negative bacilli currently in phase 2 or phase 3 clinical trials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] However, these drugs did not address the entire spectrum of resistance of Gram-negative bacilli.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] According to the WHO fifty one new therapeutic entities - antibiotics (including combinations), are in phase 1–3 clinical trials as of May 2017.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antibiotics targeting multidrug-resistant Gram-positive pathogens remains a high priority.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] A few antibiotics have received marketing authorization in the last seven years.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The cephalosporin ceftaroline and the lipoglycopeptides oritavancin and telavancin have been approved for the treatment of acute bacterial skin and skin structure infection and community-acquired bacterial pneumonia.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The lipoglycopeptide dalbavancin and the oxazolidinone tedizolid has also been approved for use for the treatment of acute bacterial skin and skin structure infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The first in a new class of narrow-spectrum macrocyclic antibiotics, fidaxomicin, has been approved for the treatment of *C. difficile* colitis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] New cephalosporin-lactamase inhibitor combinations also approved include ceftazidime-avibactam and ceftolozane-avibactam for complicated urinary tract infection and intra-abdominal infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Possible improvements include clarification of clinical trial regulations by FDA.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Furthermore, appropriate economic incentives could persuade pharmaceutical companies to invest in this endeavor.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] In the US, the Antibiotic Development to Advance Patient Treatment (ADAPT) Act was introduced with the aim of fast tracking the drug development of antibiotics to combat the growing threat of 'superbugs'.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Under this Act, FDA can approve antibiotics and antifungals treating life-threatening infections based on smaller clinical trials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The CDC will monitor the use of antibiotics and the emerging resistance, and publish the data.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The FDA antibiotics labeling process, 'Susceptibility Test Interpretive Criteria for Microbial Organisms' or 'breakpoints', will provide accurate data to healthcare professionals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Because antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains continue to emerge and spread, there is a constant need to develop new antibacterial treatments.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Bacteria, fungi, plants, animals and other organisms are being screened in the search for new antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Most of the antibiotics in current use are natural products or natural product derivatives, and bacterial, fungal, plant and animal extracts are being screened in the search for new antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Organisms may be selected for testing based on ecological, ethnomedical, genomic, or historical rationales.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Medicinal plants, for example, are screened on the basis that they are used by traditional healers to prevent or cure infection and may therefore contain antibacterial compounds.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Also, soil bacteria are screened on the basis that, historically, they have been a very rich source of antibiotics (with 70 to 80% of antibiotics in current use derived from the actinomycetes).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] In addition to screening natural products for direct antibacterial activity, they are sometimes screened for the ability to suppress antibiotic resistance and antibiotic tolerance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] For example, some secondary metabolites inhibit drug efflux pumps, thereby increasing the concentration of antibiotic able to reach its cellular target and decreasing bacterial resistance to the antibiotic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Natural products known to inhibit bacterial efflux pumps include the alkaloid lysergol, the carotenoids capsanthin and capsorubin, and the flavonoids rotenone and chrysin.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Other natural products, this time primary metabolites rather than secondary metabolites, have been shown to eradicate antibiotic tolerance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] For example, glucose, mannitol, and fructose reduce antibiotic tolerance in *Escherichia coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*, rendering them more susceptible to killing by aminoglycoside antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Natural products may be screened for the ability to suppress bacterial virulence factors too.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Examples of natural products with antivirulence activity include the flavonoid epigallocatechin gallate (which inhibits listeriolysin O), the quinone tetrangomycin (which inhibits staphyloxanthin), and the sesquiterpene zerumbone (which inhibits *Acinetobacter baumannii* motility).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antibodies (anti-tetanus immunoglobulin) have been used in the treatment and prevention of tetanus since the 1910s, and this approach continues to be a useful way of controlling bacterial diseases.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The monoclonal antibody bezlotoxumab, for example, has been approved by the US FDA and EMA for recurrent Clostridioides difficile infection, and other monoclonal antibodies are in development (e.g.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] AR-301 for the adjunctive treatment of *S. aureus* ventilator-associated pneumonia).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antibody treatments act by binding to and neutralizing bacterial exotoxins and other virulence factors.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Phage therapy is under investigation as a method of treating antibiotic-resistant strains of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Phage therapy involves infecting bacterial pathogens with viruses.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Bacteriophages and their host ranges are extremely specific for certain bacteria, thus, unlike antibiotics, they do not disturb the host organism's intestinal microbiota.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Bacteriophages, also known as phages, infect and kill bacteria primarily during lytic cycles.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Phages insert their DNA into the bacterium, where it is transcribed and used to make new phages, after which the cell will lyse, releasing new phage that are able to infect and destroy further bacteria of the same strain.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The high specificity of phage protects "good" bacteria from destruction.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Some disadvantages to the use of bacteriophages also exist, however.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Bacteriophages may harbour virulence factors or toxic genes in their genomes and, prior to use, it may be prudent to identify genes with similarity to known virulence factors or toxins by genomic sequencing.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] In addition, the oral and IV administration of phages for the eradication of bacterial infections poses a much higher safety risk than topical application.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Also, there is the additional concern of uncertain immune responses to these large antigenic cocktails.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] There are considerable regulatory hurdles that must be cleared for such therapies.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Despite numerous challenges, the use of bacteriophages as a replacement for antimicrobial agents against MDR pathogens that no longer respond to conventional antibiotics, remains an attractive option.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Fecal microbiota transplants involve transferring the full intestinal microbiota from a healthy human donor (in the form of stool) to patients with *C. difficile* infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Although this procedure has not been officially approved by the US FDA, its use is permitted under some conditions in patients with antibiotic-resistant *C. difficile* infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Cure rates are around 90%, and work is underway to develop stool banks, standardized products, and methods of oral delivery.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Fecal microbiota transplantation has also been used more recently for inflammatory bowel diseases.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The antisense RNA then hybridizes with the bacterial mRNA and blocks its translation into the essential protein.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antisense RNA-based treatment has been shown to be effective in *in vivo* models of *P. aeruginosa* pneumonia.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] In addition to silencing essential bacterial genes, antisense RNA can be used to silence bacterial genes responsible for antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] For example, antisense RNA has been developed that silences the *S. aureus* *mecA* gene (the gene that encodes modified penicillin-binding protein 2a and renders *S. aureus* strains methicillin-resistant).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antisense RNA targeting *mecA* mRNA has been shown to restore the susceptibility of methicillin-resistant staphylococci to oxacillin in both *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] In the early 2000s, a system was discovered that enables bacteria to defend themselves against invading viruses.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The system, known as CRISPR-Cas9, consists of (a) an enzyme that destroys DNA (the nuclease Cas9) and (b) the DNA sequences of previously encountered viral invaders (CRISPR).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] These viral DNA sequences enable the nuclease to target foreign (viral) rather than self (bacterial) DNA.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Although the function of CRISPR-Cas9 in nature is to protect bacteria, the DNA sequences in the CRISPR component of the system can be modified so that the Cas9 nuclease targets bacterial resistance genes or bacterial virulence genes instead of viral genes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] The modified CRISPR-Cas9 system can then be administered to bacterial pathogens using plasmids or bacteriophages.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] This approach has successfully been used to silence antibiotic resistance and reduce the virulence of enterohemorrhagic *E. coli* in an *in vivo* model of infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] In addition to developing new antibacterial treatments, it is important to reduce the selection pressure for the emergence and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR), such as antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antibiotic cycling, where antibiotics are alternated by clinicians to treat microbial diseases, is proposed, but recent studies revealed such strategies are ineffective against antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Vaccines are an essential part of the response to reduce AMR as they prevent infections, reduce the use and overuse of antimicrobials, and slow the emergence and spread of drug-resistant pathogens.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Vaccination either excites or reinforces the immune competence of a host to ward off infection, leading to the activation of macrophages, the production of antibodies, inflammation, and other classic immune reactions.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-p02] Antibacterial vaccines have been responsible for a drastic reduction in global bacterial diseases.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a serious result of AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Resistance arises through spontaneous mutation, horizontal gene transfer, and increased selective pressure from antibiotic overuse, both in medicine and agriculture, which accelerates resistance development.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Preventive measures, such as using narrow-spectrum antibiotics and improving hygiene practices, aim to reduce the spread of resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) claims that AMR is one of the top global public health and development threats, estimating that bacterial AMR was directly responsible for 1.27 million global deaths in 2019 and contributed to 4.95 million deaths.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The burden of AMR is immense, with nearly 5 million annual deaths associated with resistant infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Infections from AMR microbes are more challenging to treat and often require costly alternative therapies that may have more severe side effects.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Moreover, the WHO and other international bodies warn that AMR could lead to up to 10 million deaths annually by 2050 unless actions are taken.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Global initiatives, such as calls for international AMR treaties, emphasize coordinated efforts to limit misuse, fund research, and provide access to necessary antimicrobials in developing nations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, the COVID-19 pandemic redirected resources and scientific attention away from AMR, intensifying the challenge.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance means that a microorganism is resistant to an antimicrobial drug that was once able to treat an infection by that microorganism.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Resistance is a property of the microbe, not a person or other organism infected by a microbe.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] All types of microbes can develop drug resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Thus, there are antibiotic, antifungal, antiviral and antiparasitic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a subset of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This more specific resistance is linked to bacteria and thus broken down into two further subsets, microbiological and clinical.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Microbiological resistance is the most common and occurs from genes, mutated or inherited, that allow the bacteria to resist the mechanism to kill the microbe associated with certain antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Clinical resistance is shown through the failure of many therapeutic techniques where the bacteria that are normally susceptible to a treatment become resistant after surviving the outcome of the treatment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In both cases of acquired resistance, the bacteria can pass the genetic catalyst for resistance through horizontal gene transfer: conjugation, transduction, or transformation.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This allows the resistance to spread across the same species of pathogen or even similar bacterial pathogens.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] WHO report released April 2014 stated, "this serious threat is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2024, nearly 5 million deaths were associated with AMR and deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] One in five people who died due to AMR were children under five years old.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2018, WHO considered antibiotic resistance to be one of the biggest threats to global health, food security and development.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control calculated that in 2015 there were 671,689 infections in the EU and European Economic Area caused by antibiotic-resistant bacteria, resulting in 33,110 deaths.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Most were acquired in healthcare settings.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2019 there were 133,000 deaths caused by AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] They reproduce and spread quickly, and they also can adapt to their environment and change how well they can survive.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This leads to microbes either evolving a defense against drugs used to treat them, or certain strains of microbes that have a natural resistance to antimicrobials becoming much more prevalent than the ones that are easily defeated with medication.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Genetic changes can also occur, which would allow the microbe to survive.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] While antimicrobial resistance does occur naturally over time, the use of antimicrobial agents in a variety of settings both within the healthcare industry and outside of has led to antimicrobial resistance becoming increasingly more prevalent.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Although many microbes develop resistance to antibiotics over time through natural mutation, overprescribing and inappropriate prescription of antibiotics have accelerated the problem.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] During mutation, when replication happens, these mutations help individual microbes survive exposure.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] (NIAID, 2025) It is possible that as many as 1 in 3 prescriptions written for antibiotics are unnecessary.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Every year, approximately 154 million prescriptions for antibiotics are written.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Of these, up to 46 million are unnecessary or inappropriate for the condition that the patient has.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Microbes may naturally develop resistance through genetic mutations that occur during cell division, and although random mutations are rare, many microbes reproduce frequently and rapidly, increasing the chances of members of the population acquiring a mutation that increases resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In contrast to that, recent research suggests that, contrary to the traditional model of rapid genetic mutation, mycobacteria maintain high genomic stability under antibiotic pressure, relying instead on phenotypic tolerance and DNA-repair mechanisms for survival.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Many individuals stop taking antibiotics when they begin to feel better.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] When this occurs, it is possible that the microbes that are less susceptible to treatment still remain in the body.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] If these microbes are able to continue to reproduce, this can lead to an infection by bacteria that are less susceptible or even resistant to an antibiotic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Microbes may also get genes from each other, which makes them drug-resistant.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Bacteria that have drug-resistant DNA often transfer a copy of these genes to the other bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This process, known as horizontal gene transfer, allows resistance genes to spread rapidly between different bacterial species through mechanisms such as conjugation, transformation, and transduction.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Bacteria become resistant to antibiotics by changing themselves or acquiring resistance genes from other bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Over the past 20 years, antimicrobial resistance (AMR) has grown, making common infections like respiratory infections, urinary tract infections, STDs, and tuberculosis harder to treat.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] New antibiotics are not being developed fast enough and may lead to a "post-antibiotic era" where some infections are untreatable.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] AMR makes infections more difficult and costly to treat.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Proper antibiotic use—correct drug, dose, and duration—and strict hospital hygiene are essential.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Combating AMR requires cooperation among governments, healthcare workers, researchers, pharmaceutical companies, farmers, and the public through responsible antibiotic use, monitoring resistance, limiting antibiotics in animals, and improving access to medicines, vaccines, and tests.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Prevention is the most effective strategy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Along with careful antibiotic use, there is a need for new drugs, alternative treatments, better diagnostics, and vaccines.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Without coordinated global action, vital medical procedures like surgery, organ transplants, neonatal care, and cancer treatment could be at risk.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can evolve naturally due to continued exposure to antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Natural selection means that organisms that are able to adapt to their environment, survive, and continue to produce offspring.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] As a result, the types of microorganisms that are able to survive over time with continued attack by certain antimicrobial agents will naturally become more prevalent in the environment, and those without this resistance will become obsolete.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Some contemporary antimicrobial resistances have also evolved naturally before the use of antimicrobials of human clinical uses.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] For instance, methicillin-resistance evolved as a pathogen of hedgehogs, possibly as a co-evolutionary adaptation of the pathogen to hedgehogs that are infected by a dermatophyte that naturally produces antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Also, many soil fungi and bacteria are natural competitors and the original antibiotic penicillin discovered by Alexander Fleming rapidly lost clinical effectiveness in treating humans and, furthermore, none of the other natural penicillins (F, K, N, X, O, U1 or U6) are currently in clinical use.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can be acquired from other microbes through swapping genes in a process termed horizontal gene transfer.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This means that once a gene for resistance to an antibiotic appears in a microbial community, it can then spread to other microbes, potentially moving from a non-disease causing microbe to a disease-causing microbe.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This process is heavily driven by the natural selection processes that happen during antibiotic use or misuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Over time, most of the strains of bacteria and infections present will be the type resistant to the antimicrobial agent being used to treat them, making this agent now ineffective to defeat most microbes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] With the increased use of antimicrobial agents, there is a speeding up of this natural process.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In the vast majority of countries, antibiotics can only be prescribed by a doctor and supplied by a pharmacy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Self-medication by consumers is defined as "the taking of medicines on one's own initiative or on another person's suggestion, who is not a certified medical professional", and it has been identified as one of the primary reasons for the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Self-medication with antibiotics is an unsuitable way of using them but a common practice in resource-constrained countries.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The practice exposes individuals to the risk of bacteria that have developed antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Many people resort to this out of necessity, when access to a physician is unavailable, or when patients have a limited amount of time or money to see a doctor.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This increased access makes it extremely easy to obtain antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] An example is India, where in the state of Punjab 73% of the population resorted to treating their minor health issues and chronic illnesses through self-medication.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Self-medication is higher outside the hospital environment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The prevalence of self-medication in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs) ranges from 8.1% to 93%.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Accessibility, affordability, and conditions of health facilities, as well as the health-seeking behavior, are factors that influence self-medication in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] To determine the public's knowledge and preconceived notions on antibiotic resistance, a screening of 3,537 articles published in Europe, Asia, and North America was done.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Of the 55,225 total people surveyed in the articles, 70% had heard of antibiotic resistance previously, but 88% of those people thought it referred to some type of physical change in the human body.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Clinical misuse by healthcare professionals is another contributor to increased antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Studies done in the US show that the indication for treatment of antibiotics, choice of the agent used, and the duration of therapy was incorrect in up to 50% of the cases studied.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In 2010 and 2011 about a third of antibiotic prescriptions in outpatient settings in the United States were not necessary.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Another study in an intensive care unit in a major hospital in France has shown that 30% to 60% of prescribed antibiotics were unnecessary.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These inappropriate uses of antimicrobial agents promote the evolution of antimicrobial resistance by supporting the bacteria in developing genetic alterations that lead to resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This demonstrates that many doctors underestimate the impact that their own prescribing habits have on antimicrobial resistance as a whole.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] It also confirms that some physicians may be overly cautious and prescribe antibiotics for both medical or legal reasons, even when clinical indications for use of these medications are not always confirmed.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This can lead to unnecessary antimicrobial use, a pattern which may have worsened during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Important to the conversation of antibiotic use is the veterinary medical system.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Veterinary oversight is required by law for all medically important antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Veterinarians use the Pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic model (PK/PD) approach to ensuring that the correct dose of the drug is delivered to the correct place at the correct timing.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Increased antibiotic use during the early waves of the COVID-19 pandemic may exacerbate this global health challenge.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Moreover, pandemic burdens on some healthcare systems may contribute to antibiotic-resistant infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The use of disinfectants such as alcohol-based hand sanitizers, and antiseptic hand wash may also have the potential to increase antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Overuse of disinfectants can lead to mutations that induce antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] On the other hand, "increased hand hygiene, decreased international travel, and decreased elective hospital procedures may have reduced AMR pathogen selection and spread in the short term" during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Critically ill patients are prone to infections, and because of that, they often require antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The more antimicrobials, the more resistance one becomes to it.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) significantly strains healthcare systems and national economies.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The World Bank estimates that by 2050, AMR could increase healthcare costs by around US$1 trillion and cause global economic losses of US$1–3.4 trillion annually by 2030.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Resistant infections are harder to treat, often requiring longer hospital stays, additional tests, and stronger, more expensive medications, placing extra pressure on hospitals and health systems, especially during pandemics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] A 2024 United Nations High-Level Meeting on AMR has pledged to reduce deaths associated with bacterial AMR by 10% over the next six years.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In their first major declaration on the issue since 2016, global leaders also committed to raising $100 million to update and implement AMR action plans.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, the final draft of the declaration omitted an earlier target to reduce antibiotic use in animals by 30% by 2030, due to opposition from meat-producing countries and the farming industry.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Critics argue this omission is a major weakness, as livestock accounts for around 73% of global sales of antimicrobial agents, including antibiotics, antivirals, and antiparasitics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Considering the complex interactions between humans, animals and the environment, it is also important to consider the environmental aspects and contributors to antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] One of these factors is human and hospital waste, which is a substantial contributor to environmental antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] It is estimated that around 50–80% of antibiotics are passed unmetabolized in urine and 4–30% in feces, causing large quantities of active antibiotics to enter sewage systems.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Sewage environments contain high levels of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria (ARB), antimicrobial resistance genes (ARGs), and mobile genetic elements such as plasmids, which enable rapid gene exchange.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) are typically not designed to remove AMR; in some cases, multidrug-resistant species such as *Escherichia, Shigella, and Klebsiella* can increase twofold in treated wastewater.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) has also been detected in both raw and treated sewage.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Agriculture is also a major contributor to environmental AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Manure from livestock (such as cattle, sheep, etc.) contains residual antibiotics, which enter the soil as farmers usually use it as fertilizer.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These are typically at levels of 1–10 mg/kg, and also contain ARBs and ARGs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] One megaton of antibiotics has been estimated to have entered global soils through manure application.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Pathogens can survive in soil for up to 10 years and on plant surfaces for up to 1 year, thereby enabling long-term environmental continuation of AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Because manure can be applied to diverse crops, residual antibiotics and resistance genes can enter plant tissues and the surrounding soil microbiota, contributing to AMR detected on fruits and vegetables.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Heavy metals in soil, often introduced through fertilizers or industrial processes, can drive cross- and co-resistance mechanisms that select for antibiotic-resistant bacteria even when no antibiotics are present.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Similar selective results happen with biocides and pesticides.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Aquaculture is an underrecognized source of environmental AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Approximately 70% of antibiotics administered in aquaculture enter surrounding waterways, and tetracycline-resistant genes have been found even in isolated environments such as Antarctica and the Arctic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotic usage varies substantially across countries, showing the major differences in regulatory oversight.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] High antibiotic use in many Asian aquaculture systems has added to the elevated levels of clinically important resistance genes in sediments and river systems.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Recent research has shown that AMR also occurs through the air.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Airborne resistance genes have been detected at high levels in major urban centers, and farms have been determined as hotspots for airborne AMR, with resistance markers detected in the air surrounding animal operations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The antimicrobial resistance crisis also extends to the food industry, specifically with food producing animals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] With an ever-increasing human population, there is constant pressure to intensify productivity in many agricultural sectors, including the production of meat as a source of protein.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotics are fed to livestock to act as growth supplements, and a preventive measure to decrease the likelihood of infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Farmers typically use antibiotics in animal feed to improve growth rates and prevent infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, this is illogical as antibiotics are used to treat infections and not prevent infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agricultural purposes and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Overusing antibiotics gives the bacteria time to adapt leaving higher doses or even stronger antibiotics needed to combat the infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Though antibiotics for growth promotion were banned throughout the EU in 2006, 40 countries still use antibiotics to promote growth.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This can result in the transfer of resistant bacterial strains into the food that humans eat, causing potentially fatal transfer of disease.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] While the practice of using antibiotics as growth promoters does result in better yields and meat products, it is a major issue and needs to be decreased to prevent antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Though the evidence linking antimicrobial usage in livestock to antimicrobial resistance is limited, the World Health Organization Advisory Group on Integrated Surveillance of Antimicrobial Resistance strongly recommended the reduction of use of medically important antimicrobials in livestock.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Additionally, the Advisory Group stated that such antimicrobials should be expressly prohibited for both growth promotion and disease prevention in food producing animals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] By mapping antimicrobial consumption in livestock, it was predicted that in 228 countries there would be a total 67% increase in consumption of antibiotics by livestock by 2030.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In some countries such as Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa it is predicted that a 99% increase will occur.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Several countries have restricted the use of antibiotics in livestock, including Canada, China, Japan, and the US.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These restrictions are sometimes associated with a reduction of the prevalence of antimicrobial resistance in humans.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Most pesticides protect crops against insects and plants, but in some cases antimicrobial pesticides are used to protect against various microorganisms such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, algae, and protozoa.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The overuse of many pesticides in an effort to have a higher yield of crops has resulted in many of these microbes evolving a tolerance against these antimicrobial agents.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Currently there are over 4000 antimicrobial pesticides registered with the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and sold to market, showing the widespread use of these agents.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] It is estimated that for every single meal a person consumes, 0.3 g of pesticides is used, as 90% of all pesticide use is in agriculture.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] A majority of these products are used to help defend against the spread of infectious diseases, and hopefully protect public health.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] But out of the large amount of pesticides used, it is also estimated that less than 0.1% of those antimicrobial agents, actually reach their targets.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] That leaves over 99% of all pesticides used available to contaminate other resources.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In soil, air, and water these antimicrobial agents are able to spread, coming in contact with more microorganisms and leading to these microbes evolving mechanisms to tolerate and further resist pesticides.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The use of antifungal azole pesticides that drive environmental azole resistance have been linked to azole resistance cases in the clinical setting.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The same issues confront the novel antifungal classes (e.g. orotomides) which are again being used in both the clinic and agriculture.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wildlife, including wild and migratory birds, serve as indicators of ecosystem health.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] They act as a reservoir for zoonotic diseases and antimicrobial-resistant organisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Birds are a key link between the transmission of zoonotic diseases to human populations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] By the same token, increased contact between wild birds and human populations (including domesticated animals), has increased the amount of anti-microbial resistance (AMR) to the bird population.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The introduction of AMR to wild birds positively correlates with human pollution and increased human contact.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Additionally, wild birds can participate in horizontal gene transfer with bacteria, leading to the transmission of antibiotic-resistant genes (ARG).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] For simplicity, wild bird populations can be divided into two major categories, wild sedentary birds and wild migrating birds.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wild sedentary bird exposure to AMR is through increased contact with densely populated areas, human waste, domestic animals, and domestic animal/livestock waste.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Especially if they are predators, wild, sedentary birds can come into contact with prey that interact more closely with humans.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Wild migrating birds interact with sedentary birds in different environments along their migration route.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This increases the rate and diversity of AMR across varying ecosystems.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Neglect of wildlife in the global discussions surrounding health security and AMR, creates large barriers to true AMR surveillance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The surveillance of antimicrobial-resistant resistant organisms in wild birds is a potential metric for the rate of AMR in the environment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] This surveillance also allows for further investigation into the transmission routes between different ecosystems and human populations (including domesticated animals and livestock).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Such information gathered from wild bird biomes, can help identify patterns of diseased transmission and better target interventions.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These targeted interventions can inform the use of antimicrobial agents and reduce the persistence of multidrug resistant organisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Recent studies demonstrate the importance of wild birds as sentinels for AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] For example, *Escherichia coli* isolated from free-ranging Bonelli's eagles (*Aquila fasciata*) in eastern Spain showed that 53.3% of isolates were resistant to at least one antimicrobial, and 29.3% were multidrug-resistant, despite the species' minimal exposure to human-associated environments.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The study also reported resistance to colistin and meropenem, two last-resort antibiotics, and documented 19 different multidrug-resistance patterns, suggesting persistent and heterogeneous selective pressures in the environment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Because Bonelli's eagles live far from humans and urban areas, they acquire resistance largely through interactions with prey species that interact with humans.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] These findings demonstrate how AMR can spread into remote ecosystems via indirect pathways, strengthening the role of wild birds, particularly apex predators, as effective bioindicators in AMR surveillance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Permafrost is a term used to refer to any ground that remained frozen for two years or more, with the oldest known examples continuously frozen for around 700,000 years.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] In the recent decades, permafrost has been rapidly thawing due to climate change.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] The cold preserves any organic matter inside the permafrost, and it is possible for microorganisms to resume their life functions once it thaws.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] While some common pathogens such as influenza, smallpox or the bacteria associated with pneumonia have failed to survive intentional attempts to revive them, more cold-adapted microorganisms such as anthrax, or several ancient plant and amoeba viruses, have successfully survived prolonged thaw.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Some scientists have argued that the inability of known causative agents of contagious diseases to survive being frozen and thawed makes this threat unlikely.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Instead, there have been suggestions that when modern pathogenic bacteria interact with the ancient ones, they may, through horizontal gene transfer, pick up genetic sequences which are associated with antimicrobial resistance, exacerbating an already difficult issue.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Antibiotics to which permafrost bacteria have displayed at least some resistance include chloramphenicol, streptomycin, kanamycin, gentamicin, tetracycline, spectinomycin and neomycin.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] However, other studies show that resistance levels in ancient bacteria to modern antibiotics remain lower than in the contemporary bacteria from the active layer of thawed ground above them, which may mean that this risk is "no greater" than from any other soil.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] There have been increasing public calls for global collective action to address the threat, including a proposal for an international treaty on antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] Further detail and attention is still needed to recognize and measure trends in resistance on the international level; the idea of a global tracking system has been suggested but implementation has yet to occur.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p01] A system of this nature would provide insight to areas of high resistance as well as information necessary for evaluating programs, introducing interventions and other changes made to fight or reverse antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) is commonly described within a *One Health* framework, which emphasizes the interconnected relationships between human health, animal health, and the environment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial use in clinical medicine, veterinary practice, and agriculture has been associated with the selection and spread of resistant microorganisms across these sectors.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Research indicates that resistant bacteria and antimicrobial resistance genes can move between humans, animals, and environmental reservoirs through multiple pathways, including food production systems, direct contact, and exposure to contaminated water or soil.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These pathways contribute to the persistence and wider dissemination of antimicrobial resistance beyond individual settings.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Environmental sources have been increasingly examined in relation to AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Wastewater systems, agricultural runoff, and pharmaceutical residues have been identified as potential reservoirs where resistant microorganisms and resistance genes may persist.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Such reservoirs may facilitate ongoing transmission between environmental, animal, and human populations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Efforts to address AMR within a One Health framework typically involve coordinated strategies across sectors, including antimicrobial stewardship, infection prevention and control, and improvements in sanitation and hygiene.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Evidence from systematic reviews suggests that interventions such as farm biosecurity and water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) practices may reduce antimicrobial use and contribute to limiting the development and spread of resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Delaying or minimizing the use of antibiotics for certain conditions may help safely reduce their use.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial treatment duration should be based on the infection and other health problems a person may have.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For many infections once a person has improved there is little evidence that stopping treatment causes more resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some, therefore, feel that stopping early may be reasonable in some cases.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Other infections, however, do require long courses regardless of whether a person feels better.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Delaying antibiotics for ailments such as a sore throat and otitis media may have no difference in the rate of complications compared with immediate antibiotics, for example.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] When treating respiratory tract infections, clinical judgement is required as to the appropriate treatment (delayed or immediate antibiotic use).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] ResistanceOpen is an online global map of antimicrobial resistance developed by HealthMap which displays aggregated data on antimicrobial resistance from publicly available and user submitted data.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The website can display data for a 25 miles (40 km) radius from a location.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Users may submit data from antibiograms for individual hospitals or laboratories.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] European data is from the EARS-Net (European Antimicrobial Resistance Surveillance Network), part of the ECDC.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] ResistanceMap is a website by the Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy and provides data on antimicrobial resistance on a global level.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO's AMR global action plan also recommends antimicrobial resistance surveillance in animals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Initial steps in the EU for establishing the veterinary counterpart EARS-Vet (EARS-Net for veterinary medicine) have been made.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] AMR data from pets in particular is scarce, but needed to support antibiotic stewardship in veterinary medicine.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] By comparison there is a lack of national and international monitoring programs for antifungal resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship programmes appear useful in reducing rates of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The antimicrobial stewardship program will also provide pharmacists with the knowledge to educate patients that antibiotics will not work for a virus for example.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Excessive antimicrobial use has become one of the top contributors to the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Since the beginning of the antimicrobial era, antimicrobials have been used to treat a wide range of infectious diseases.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Overuse of antimicrobials has become the primary cause of rising levels of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Prescribers are willing to prescribe antimicrobials to individuals who believe that antimicrobials can cure nearly all illnesses, including viral infections like the common cold.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In an analysis of drug prescriptions, 36% of individuals with a cold or an upper respiratory infection (both usually viral in origin) were given prescriptions for antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These prescriptions increase the risk of further evolution of antibiotic resistant bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Using antimicrobials without prescription is another driving force leading to the overuse of antibiotics to self-treat diseases like the common cold, cough, fever, and dysentery resulting in an epidemic of antibiotic resistance in countries like Bangladesh, risking its spread around the globe.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Introducing strict antibiotic stewardship in the outpatient setting to reduce inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics may reduce the emerging bacterial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO AWaRe (Access, Watch, Reserve) guidance and antibiotic book has been introduced to guide antibiotic choice for the 30 most common infections in adults and children to reduce inappropriate prescribing in primary care and hospitals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Narrow-spectrum antibiotics are preferred due to their lower resistance potential, and broad-spectrum antibiotics are only recommended for people with more severe symptoms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some antibiotics are more likely to confer resistance, so are kept as reserve antibiotics in the AWaRe book.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Various diagnostic strategies have been employed to prevent the overuse of antifungal therapy in the clinic, proving a safe alternative to empirical antifungal therapy, and thus underpinning antifungal stewardship schemes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship teams in hospitals are encouraging optimal use of antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The goals of antimicrobial stewardship are to help practitioners pick the right drug at the right dose and duration of therapy while preventing misuse and minimizing the development of resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Stewardship interventions may reduce the length of stay by an average of slightly over 1 day while not increasing the risk of death.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Dispensing the exact number of antibiotic pharmaceutical units necessary to complete an ongoing treatment can reduce excess antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A 2025 cross-sectional study of 125 pharmacists at a UK NHS Foundation Trust examined knowledge, attitudes, and perceptions regarding antimicrobial stewardship following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The study found that more than 85% of pharmacists recognized antimicrobial resistance as a public health concern.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, the pandemic created challenges, with 80% reporting that COVID-19 patient conditions influenced antibiotic prescription.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A 2026 systematic review of 73 studies examined arthropod-mediated pathogen transmission in hospitals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Research indicates that cockroaches, flies, and ants frequently harbor multidrug-resistant bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] While direct causality is difficult to prove, genetic evidence links these pests to hospital-associated infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Given the volume of care provided in primary care (general practice), recent strategies have focused on reducing unnecessary antimicrobial prescribing in this setting.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Simple interventions, such as written information explaining when taking antibiotics is not necessary, for example in common infections of the upper respiratory tract, have been shown to reduce antibiotic prescribing.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Various tools are also available to help professionals decide if prescribing antimicrobials is necessary.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Parental expectations, driven by the worry for their children's health, can influence how often children are prescribed antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Parents often rely on their clinician for advice and reassurance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However a lack of plain language information and not having adequate time for consultation negatively impacts this relationship.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In effect parents often rely on past experiences in their expectations rather than reassurance from the clinician.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Adequate time for consultation and plain language information can help parents make informed decisions and avoid unnecessary antibiotic use.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The prescriber should closely adhere to the five rights of drug administration: the right patient, the right drug, the right dose, the right route, and the right time.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Microbiological samples should be taken for culture and sensitivity testing before treatment when indicated and treatment potentially changed based on the susceptibility report.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Health workers and pharmacists can help tackle antibiotic resistance by: enhancing infection prevention and control; only prescribing and dispensing antibiotics when they are truly needed; prescribing and dispensing the right antibiotic(s) to treat the illness.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A unit dose system implemented in community pharmacies can also reduce antibiotic leftovers at households.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Despite these, written guideline intervention for prescriber to do history taking and provision of advice and knowledge of pharmacists and non‐pharmacists may not reduce the sales of non‐prescription antimicrobial drugs in community pharmacies, drugstores, and other medicine outlets.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] People can help tackle resistance by using antibiotics only when prescribed for a bacterial infetion as well as completing the full treatment course, never sharing medication with others, and using proper disposal methods for excess drugs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Basic hygiene practices also help prevent the spread of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] • Germany and Sweden also have lower prescribing rates, with Sweden's rate having been declining since 2007. • Greece, France and Belgium have high prescribing rates.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Infectious disease control through improved water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) infrastructure needs to be included in the antimicrobial resistance (AMR) agenda.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Growing usage of antibiotics together with persistent infectious disease levels have led to a dangerous cycle in which reliance on antimicrobials increases while the efficacy of drugs diminishes.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The proper use of infrastructure for water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) can result in a 47–72 percent decrease of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics depending on the type of intervention and its effectiveness.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A reduction of the diarrhea disease burden through improved infrastructure would result in large decreases in the number of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This was estimated as ranging from 5 million in Brazil to up to 590 million in India by the year 2030.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The strong link between increased consumption and resistance indicates that this will directly mitigate the accelerating spread of AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Sanitation and water for all by 2030 is Goal Number 6 of the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] An increase in hand washing compliance by hospital staff results in decreased rates of resistant organisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Water supply and sanitation infrastructure in health facilities offer opportunities for combatting AMR, and investment should be increased.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] There is much room for improvement: WHO and UNICEF estimated in 2015 that 38% of health facilities did not have a source of water, nearly 19% had no toilets and 35% had no water and soap or alcohol-based hand rub for handwashing.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Manufacturers of antimicrobials need to improve the treatment of their wastewater (by using industrial wastewater treatment processes) to reduce the release of residues into the environment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] It is established that the use of antibiotics in animal husbandry can give rise to AMR resistances in bacteria found in food animals to the antibiotics being administered (through injections or medicated feeds).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For this reason only antimicrobials that are deemed "not-clinically relevant" are used in these practices.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Unlike resistance to antibacterials, antifungal resistance can be driven by arable farming, currently there is no regulation on the use of similar antifungal classes in agriculture and the clinic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Recent studies have shown that the prophylactic use of "non-priority" or "non-clinically relevant" antimicrobials in feeds can potentially, under certain conditions, lead to co-selection of environmental AMR bacteria with resistance to medically important antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The possibility for co-selection of AMR resistances in the food chain pipeline may have far-reaching implications for human health.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 1997, European Union health ministers voted to ban avoparcin and four additional antibiotics used to promote animal growth in 1999.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2006 a ban on the use of antibiotics in European feed, with the exception of two antibiotics in poultry feeds, became effective.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In Scandinavia, there is evidence that the ban has led to a lower prevalence of antibiotic resistance in (nonhazardous) animal bacterial populations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] As of 2004, several European countries established a decline of antimicrobial resistance in humans through limiting the use of antimicrobials in agriculture and food industries without jeopardizing animal health or economic cost.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) collect data on antibiotic use in humans and in a more limited fashion in animals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] About 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agriculture purposes, and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This gives reason for concern about the antibiotic resistance crisis in the U.S. and more reason to monitor it.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The FDA first determined in 1977 that there is evidence of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains in livestock.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The long-established practice of permitting OTC sales of antibiotics (including penicillin and other drugs) to lay animal owners for administration to their own animals nonetheless continued in all states.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2000, the FDA announced their intention to revoke approval of fluoroquinolone use in poultry production because of substantial evidence linking it to the emergence of fluoroquinolone-resistant *Campylobacter* infections in humans.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Legal challenges from the food animal and pharmaceutical industries delayed the final decision to do so until 2006.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Fluroquinolones have been banned from extra-label use in food animals in the USA since 2007.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, they are still used in treatment of companion and exotic animals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The increasing interconnectedness of the world and the fact that new classes of antibiotics have not been developed and approved for 25 years highlight the extent to which antimicrobial resistance is a global health challenge.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A global action plan to tackle the growing problem of resistance to antibiotics and other antimicrobial medicines was endorsed at the Sixty-eighth World Health Assembly in May 2015.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] One of the key objectives of the plan is to improve awareness and understanding of antimicrobial resistance through effective communication, education and training.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This global action plan developed by the World Health Organization was created to combat the issue of antimicrobial resistance and was guided by the advice of countries and key stakeholders.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO's global action plan is composed of five key objectives that can be targeted through different means, and represents countries coming together to solve a major problem that can have future health consequences.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The World Health Organization has promoted the first World Antibiotic Awareness Week running from 16 to 22 November 2015.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The aim of the week is to increase global awareness of antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] It also wants to promote the correct usage of antibiotics across all fields to prevent further instances of antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] World Antibiotic Awareness Week has been held every November since 2015.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For 2017, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), the World Health Organization (WHO) and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) are together calling for responsible use of antibiotics in humans and animals to reduce the emergence of antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2016 the Secretary-General of the United Nations convened the Interagency Coordination Group (IACG) on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The IACG worked with international organizations and experts in human, animal, and plant health to create a plan to fight antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Their report released in April 2019 focuses on the seriousness of antimicrobial resistance and the threat it poses to world health.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] It suggests five recommendations for member states to follow to tackle this increasing threat.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The **One Health** approach recognizes that human, animal, and environmental health are interconnected in the development and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Alteration of target- or binding site: for example, alteration of PBP—the binding target site of penicillins—in MRSA and other penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Another protective mechanism found among bacterial species is ribosomal protection proteins.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These proteins protect the bacterial cell from antibiotics that target the cell's ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The mechanism involves the binding of the ribosomal protection proteins to the ribosomes of the bacterial cell, which in turn changes its conformational shape.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This allows the ribosomes to continue synthesizing proteins essential to the cell while preventing antibiotics from binding to the ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Reduced drug accumulation: by decreasing drug permeability or increasing active efflux (pumping out) of the drugs across the cell surface.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These multidrug efflux pumps within the cellular membrane of certain bacterial species are used to pump antibiotics out of the cell before they are able to do any damage.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] They are often activated by a specific substrate associated with an antibiotic, as in fluoroquinolone resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Ribosome splitting and recycling: for example, drug-mediated stalling of the ribosome by lincomycin and erythromycin unstalled by a heat shock protein found in *Listeria monocytogenes*, which is a homologue of HflX from other bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Liberation of the ribosome from the drug allows further translation and consequent resistance to the drug.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] There are several different types of germs that have developed a resistance over time.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The six pathogens causing most deaths associated with resistance are *Escherichia coli*, *Staphylococcus aureus, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Acinetobacter baumannii*, and *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] They were responsible for 929,000 deaths attributable to resistance and 3.57 million deaths associated with resistance in 2019.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Penicillinase-producing *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* developed a resistance to penicillin in 1976.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Another example is Azithromycin-resistant *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, which developed a resistance to azithromycin in 2011.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In gram-negative bacteria, plasmid-mediated resistance genes produce proteins that can bind to DNA gyrase, protecting it from the action of quinolones.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Finally, mutations at key sites in DNA gyrase or topoisomerase IV can decrease their binding affinity to quinolones, decreasing the drug's effectiveness.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some bacteria are naturally resistant to certain antibiotics; for example, gram-negative bacteria are resistant to most β-lactam antibiotics due to the presence of β-lactamase.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antibiotic resistance can also be acquired as a result of either genetic mutation or horizontal gene transfer.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Although mutations are rare, with spontaneous mutations in the pathogen genome occurring at a rate of about 1 in 105 to 1 in 108 per chromosomal replication, Bacteria reproduce at a high rate, lifespans and production of new generations can be on a timescale of mere hours.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A new (de novo) mutation in a parent cell can quickly become an inherited mutation of widespread prevalence, resulting in the microevolution of a fully resistant colony.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, chromosomal mutations also confer a cost of fitness.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For example, a ribosomal mutation may protect a bacterial cell by changing the binding site of an antibiotic but may result in slower growth rate.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Moreover, some adaptive mutations can propagate not only through inheritance but also through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The most common mechanism of horizontal gene transfer is the transferring of plasmids carrying antibiotic resistance genes between bacteria of the same or different species via conjugation.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Recent findings show no necessity of large populations of bacteria for the appearance of antibiotic resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Small populations of *Escherichia coli* in an antibiotic gradient can become resistant.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Any heterogeneous environment with respect to nutrient and antibiotic gradients may facilitate antibiotic resistance in small bacterial populations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Researchers hypothesize that the mechanism of resistance evolution is based on four SNP mutations in the genome of *E. coli* produced by the gradient of antibiotic.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In one study, which has implications for space microbiology, a non-pathogenic strain *E. coli* MG1655 was exposed to trace levels of the broad spectrum antibiotic chloramphenicol, under simulated microgravity (LSMMG, or Low Shear Modeled Microgravity) over 1000 generations.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Thus, irrespective of where they are used, the use of an antibiotic would likely result in persistent resistance to that antibiotic, as well as cross-resistance to other antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In recent years, the emergence and spread of β-lactamases called carbapenemases has become a major health crisis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] One such carbapenemase is New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase 1 (NDM-1), an enzyme that makes bacteria resistant to a broad range of beta-lactam antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The most common bacteria that make this enzyme are gram-negative such as *E. coli* and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*, but the gene for NDM-1 can spread from one strain of bacteria to another by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Specific antiviral drugs are used to treat some viral infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These drugs prevent viruses from reproducing by inhibiting essential stages of the virus's replication cycle in infected cells.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antivirals are used to treat HIV, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, influenza, herpes viruses including varicella zoster virus, cytomegalovirus and Epstein–Barr virus.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] With each virus, some strains have become resistant to the administered drugs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antiviral drugs typically target key components of viral reproduction; for example, oseltamivir targets influenza neuraminidase,while guanosine analogs inhibit viral DNA polymerase.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to antivirals is thus acquired through mutations in the genes that encode the protein targets of the drugs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to HIV antivirals is problematic, and even multi-drug resistant strains have evolved.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] One source of resistance is that many current HIV drugs, including NRTIs and NNRTIs, target reverse transcriptase; however, HIV-1 reverse transcriptase is highly error prone and thus mutations conferring resistance arise rapidly.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistant strains of the HIV virus emerge rapidly if only one antiviral drug is used.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Using three or more drugs together, termed combination therapy, has helped to control this problem, but new drugs are needed because of the continuing emergence of drug-resistant HIV strains.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Infections by fungi are a cause of high morbidity and mortality in immunocompromised persons, such as those with HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis or receiving chemotherapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The fungi *Candida*, *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Aspergillus fumigatus* cause most of these infections and antifungal resistance occurs in all of them.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Multidrug resistance in fungi is increasing because of the widespread use of antifungal drugs to treat infections in immunocompromised individuals and the use of some agricultural antifungals.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistant disease is associated with increased mortality.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some fungi (for example, *Candida krusei* and fluconazole) exhibit intrinsic resistance to certain antifungal drugs or classes, whereas some species develop antifungal resistance to external pressures.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistance is a One Health concern, driven by multiple extrinsic factors, including overuse of fungicides, clinical antifungals, environmental change and host factors.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In the USA fluconazole-resistant Candida species and azole resistance in Aspergillus fumigatus have been highlighted as a growing threat.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] 20 species of *Candida* can cause candidiasis infection, the most common of which is *Candida albicans*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] *Candida* yeasts normally inhabit the skin and mucous membranes without causing infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, overgrowth of *Candida* can lead to candidiasis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] *Candida glabrata)* are becoming resistant to first-line and second-line antifungal agents such as echinocandins and azoles.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The emergence of *Candida auris* as a potential human pathogen that sometimes exhibits multi-class antifungal drug resistance is concerning and has been associated with several outbreaks.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO has released a priority fungal pathogen list, including pathogens with antifungal resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The identification of antifungal resistance is undermined by limited classical diagnosis of infection, where a culture is lacking, preventing susceptibility testing.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] National and international surveillance schemes for fungal disease and antifungal resistance are limited, hampering the understanding of the disease burden and associated resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The application of molecular testing to identify genetic markers associating with resistance may improve the identification of antifungal resistance, but the diversity of mutations associated with resistance is increasing across the fungal species causing infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In addition, a number of resistance mechanisms depend on up-regulation of selected genes (for instance reflux pumps) rather than defined mutations that are amenable to molecular detection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Due to the limited number of antifungals in clinical use and the increasing global incidence of antifungal resistance, using the existing antifungals in combination might be beneficial in some cases but further research is needed.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Similarly, other approaches that might help to combat the emergence of antifungal resistance could rely on the development of host-directed therapies such as immunotherapy or vaccines.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The protozoan parasites that cause the diseases malaria, trypanosomiasis, toxoplasmosis, cryptosporidiosis and leishmaniasis are important human pathogens.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Malarial parasites that are resistant to the drugs that are currently available to infections are common and this has led to increased efforts to develop new drugs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to recently developed drugs such as artemisinin has also been reported.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The problem of drug resistance in malaria has driven efforts to develop vaccines.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Trypanosomes are parasitic protozoa that cause African trypanosomiasis and Chagas disease (American trypanosomiasis).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] There are no vaccines to prevent these infections so drugs such as pentamidine and suramin, benznidazole and nifurtimox are used to treat infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] These drugs are effective but infections caused by resistant parasites have been reported.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Leishmaniasis is caused by protozoa and is a public health problem in sub-tropical and tropical countries.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Drug resistance has "become a major concern".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The preferred treatment for leishmaniasis regionally; liposomal amphotericin B is used in the Mediterranean basin and pentavalent antimonials are more commonly used in Africa, South America, Bangladesh, India, and Nepal.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Resistance to antibiotics in *Leishmania* is a relatively recent phenomena.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The first reported instance of resistance to antimonials was reported in India in the 1980s.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2022, genomic epidemiologists reported results from a global survey of antimicrobial resistance via genomic wastewater-based epidemiology, finding large regional variations, providing maps, and suggesting resistance genes are also passed on between microbial species that are not closely related.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The WHO provides the Global Antimicrobial Resistance and Use Surveillance System (GLASS) reports which summarize annual (e.g.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] 2020's) data on international AMR, also including an interactive dashboard.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Public Health England reported that the total number of antibiotic resistant infections in England rose by 9% from 55,812 in 2017 to 60,788 in 2018, but antibiotic consumption had fallen by 9% from 20.0 to 18.2 defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day between 2014 and 2018.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that 2.8 million cases of antibiotic resistance have been reported.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, in 2019 overall deaths from antibiotic-resistant infections decreased by 18% and deaths in hospitals decreased by 30%.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The COVID pandemic caused a reversal of much of the progress made on attenuating the effects of antibiotic resistance, resulting in more antibiotic use, more resistant infections, and less data on preventive action.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Hospital-onset infections and deaths both increased by 15% in 2020, and significantly higher rates of infections were reported for 4 out of 6 types of healthcare associated infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Owing to rampant misuse, over-prescription, and unregulated over-the-counter access to antibiotics, the growth of AMR superbugs has proliferated in India.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Pharmacies surveyed by the Karnataka government revealed that 80% of drugs were being sold without a prescription.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2019, India reported 300,000 deaths because of infections relating to AMR, India also reports the most number of tuberculosis cases resistant to antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The 1950s to 1970s represented the golden age of antibiotic discovery, where countless new classes of antibiotics were discovered to treat previously incurable diseases such as tuberculosis and syphilis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] However, since that time the discovery of new classes of antibiotics has been almost nonexistent, and represents a situation that is especially problematic considering the resiliency of bacteria shown over time and the continued misuse and overuse of antibiotics in treatment.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Already in 1940, in their letter to the editor of Nature journal, Abraham and Chain identified the enzyme penicillinase as responsible for the deactivation of penicillin in penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This discovery was the first step in understanding the mechanisms of microbial resistance to β-lactam antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The phenomenon of antimicrobial resistance caused by overuse of antibiotics was predicted as early as 1945 by Alexander Fleming who said "The time may come when penicillin can be bought by anyone in the shops.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance can lead to epidemics of enormous proportions if preventive actions are not taken.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In this day and age current antimicrobial resistance leads to longer hospital stays, higher medical costs, and increased mortality.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Since the mid-1980s pharmaceutical companies have invested in medications for cancer or chronic disease that have greater potential to make money and have "de-emphasized or dropped development of antibiotics".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] On 20 January 2016 at the World Economic Forum, "80 pharmaceutical and diagnostic companies" called for "transformational commercial models" at an international level to spur research and development on antibiotics and on the use of diagnostic tests.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A number of countries are considering or implementing delinked payment models for new antimicrobials whereby payment is based on value rather than volume of drug sales.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This offers the opportunity to pay for valuable new drugs even if they are reserved for use in relatively rare drug resistant infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Some global health scholars have argued that a global, legal framework is needed to prevent and control antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For instance, binding global policies could be used to create antimicrobial use standards, regulate antibiotic marketing, and strengthen global surveillance systems.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Ensuring compliance of involved parties is a challenge.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] For the United States 2016 budget, U.S. president Barack Obama proposed to nearly double the amount of federal funding to "combat and prevent" antibiotic resistance to $1.2 billion.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Many international funding agencies like USAID, DFID, Sida and Gates Foundation have pledged money for developing strategies to counter antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] On 27 March 2015, the White House released a plan to address the increasing need for agencies to combat the rise of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Task Force for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria developed *The National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria* with the intent of providing a roadmap to guide the US in the antibiotic resistance challenge and with hopes of saving many lives.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This plan outlines steps taken by the Federal government over the next five years needed to prevent and contain outbreaks of antibiotic-resistant infections; maintain the efficacy of antibiotics already on the market; and to help to develop future diagnostics, antibiotics, and vaccines.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Action Plan was developed around five goals with focuses on strengthening health care, public health veterinary medicine, agriculture, food safety and research, and manufacturing.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] As of 2023, AMR remains a public health threat in the United States.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's 2023 Report on Antibiotic Resistance Threats, over 2.8 million antibiotic-resistant infections occur in the U.S. each year, leading to at least 35,000 deaths annually.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Among the most concerning resistant pathogens are Carbapenem-resistant *Enterobacteriaceae* (CRE), Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA), and *Clostridioides difficile* (C. diff), all of which continue to be responsible for severe healthcare-associated infections (HAIs).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a disruption in healthcare, with an increase in the use of antibiotics during the treatment of viral infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This rise in antibiotic prescribing, coupled with overwhelmed healthcare systems, contributed to a resurgence in AMR during the pandemic years.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] A 2021 CDC report identified a sharp increase in HAIs caused by resistant pathogens in COVID-19 patients, a trend that has persisted into 2023.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Recent data suggest that although antibiotic use has decreased since the pandemic, some resistant pathogens remain prevalent in healthcare settings.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The CDC has also expanded its Get Ahead of Sepsis campaign in 2023, focusing on raising awareness of AMR's role in sepsis and promoting the judicious use of antibiotics in both healthcare and community settings.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This initiative has reached millions through social media, healthcare facilities, and public health outreach, aiming to educate the public on the importance of preventing infections and reducing antibiotic misuse.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Trump, severe federal funding cuts in 2025 at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and many other research entities in the United States are expected to impede progress in combating antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Public health experts believe these budget reductions will adversely affect the development of new antibiotics as well as advances in diagnostics and treatment strategies, thus undermining efforts currently underway to address AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) is but one organization that has expressed grave concern regarding the negative consequences of such extreme budget measures on antimicrobial stewardship, and, as a result, on global health security overall.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] According to World Health Organization, policymakers can help tackle resistance by strengthening resistance-tracking and laboratory capacity and by regulating and promoting the appropriate use of medicines.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Policymakers and industry can help tackle resistance by: fostering research and development of new tools and promoting cooperation and information sharing among all stakeholders.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The U.S. government continues to prioritize AMR mitigation through policy and legislation.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In 2023, the National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria (CARB) 2023-2028 was released, outlining strategic objectives for reducing antibiotic-resistant infections, advancing infection prevention, and accelerating research on new antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] The plan also emphasizes the importance of improving antibiotic stewardship across healthcare, agriculture, and veterinary settings.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Furthermore, the PASTEUR Act (Pioneering Antimicrobial Subscriptions to End Upsurging Resistance) has gained momentum in Congress.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] If passed, the bill would create a subscription-based payment model to incentivize the development of new antimicrobial drugs, while supporting antimicrobial stewardship programs to reduce the misuse of existing antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] This legislation is considered a critical step toward addressing the economic barriers to developing new antimicrobials.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] Measuring the costs and benefits of strategies to combat AMR is difficult and policies may only have effects in the distant future.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] In other infectious diseases this problem has been addressed by using mathematical models.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p02] More research is needed to understand how AMR develops and spreads so that mathematical modelling can be used to anticipate the likely effects of different policies.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Distinguishing infections requiring antibiotics from self-limiting ones is clinically challenging.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] To guide appropriate use of antibiotics and prevent the evolution and spread of antimicrobial resistance, diagnostic tests that provide clinicians with timely, actionable results are needed.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Acute fever is a common reason for seeking medical care and a major cause of morbidity and mortality.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Multiple studies have shown that the use of malaria rapid diagnostic tests without reliable tools to distinguish other fever causes has resulted in increased antibiotic use.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) can facilitate a precision medicine approach to treatment by helping clinicians to prescribe more effective and targeted antimicrobial therapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] At the same time with traditional phenotypic AST it can take 12 to 48 hours to obtain a result due to the time taken for organisms to grow on/in culture media.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Rapid testing, possible from molecular diagnostics innovations, is defined as "being feasible within an 8-h working shift".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] There are several commercial Food and Drug Administration-approved assays available which can detect AMR genes from a variety of specimen types.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Progress has been slow due to a range of reasons including cost and regulation.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Genotypic AMR characterisation methods are, however, being increasingly used in combination with machine learning algorithms in research to help better predict phenotypic AMR from organism genotype.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Optical techniques such as phase contrast microscopy in combination with single-cell analysis are another powerful method to monitor bacterial growth.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In 2017, scientists from Uppsala University in Sweden published a method that applies principles of microfluidics and cell tracking, to monitor bacterial response to antibiotics in less than 30 minutes overall manipulation time.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] This invention was awarded the 8M£ Longitude Prize on AMR in 2024.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Recently, this platform has been advanced by coupling microfluidic chip with optical tweezing to isolate bacteria with altered phenotype directly from the analytical matrix.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Rapid diagnostic methods have also been trialled as antimicrobial stewardship interventions to influence the healthcare drivers of AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Serum procalcitonin measurement has been shown to reduce mortality rate, antimicrobial consumption and antimicrobial-related side-effects in patients with respiratory infections, but impact on AMR has not yet been demonstrated.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Similarly, point of care serum testing of the inflammatory biomarker C-reactive protein has been shown to influence antimicrobial prescribing rates in this patient cohort, but further research is required to demonstrate an effect on rates of AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Clinical investigation to rule out bacterial infections are often done for patients with pediatric acute respiratory infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Currently it is unclear if rapid viral testing affects antibiotic use in children.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Microorganisms usually do not develop resistance to vaccines because vaccines reduce the spread of the infection and target the pathogen in multiple ways in the same host and possibly in different ways between different hosts.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Furthermore, if the use of vaccines increases, there is evidence that antibiotic resistant strains of pathogens will decrease; the need for antibiotics will naturally decrease as vaccines prevent infection before it occurs.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] A 2024 report by WHO finds that vaccines against 24 pathogens could reduce the number of antibiotics needed by 22% or 2.5 billion DDD every year.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] If vaccines could be rolled out against all the evaluated pathogens, they could save a third of the hospital costs associated with AMR.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Vaccinated people have fewer infections and are protected against potential complications from secondary infections that may need antimicrobial medicines or require admission to hospital.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] However, there are well documented cases of vaccine resistance, although these are usually much less of a problem than antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Antistaphylococcal vaccines have shown limited efficacy, because of immunological variation between *Staphylococcus* species, and the limited duration of effectiveness of the antibodies produced.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Development and testing of more effective vaccines is underway.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Two registrational trials have evaluated vaccine candidates in active immunization strategies against *S. aureus* infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In a phase II trial, a bivalent vaccine of capsular proteins 5 & 8 was tested in 1804 hemodialysis patients with a primary fistula or synthetic graft vascular access.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] After 40 weeks following vaccination a protective effect was seen against *S. aureus* bacteremia, but not at 54 weeks following vaccination.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Based on these results, a second trial was conducted which failed to show efficacy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Merck tested V710, a vaccine targeting IsdB, in a blinded randomized trial in patients undergoing median sternotomy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The trial was terminated after a higher rate of multiorgan system failure–related deaths was found in the V710 recipients.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Vaccine recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection were five times more likely to die than control recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Investigators have suggested that a multiple-antigen vaccine would be more effective, but a lack of biomarkers defining human protective immunity keep these proposals in the logical, but strictly hypothetical arena.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Antibodies show evidence against antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) target bacterial virulence factors, aiding in bacterial destruction through various mechanisms.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Three FDA-approved antibodies target *Bacillus anthracis* and *Clostridioides difficile* toxins.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Alternating therapy is a proposed method in which two or three antibiotics are taken in a rotation versus taking just one antibiotic such that bacteria resistant to one antibiotic are killed when the next antibiotic is taken.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Studies have found that this method reduces the rate at which antibiotic resistant bacteria emerge in vitro relative to a single drug for the entire duration.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Studies have found that bacteria that evolve antibiotic resistance towards one group of antibiotic may become more sensitive to others.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] This phenomenon can be used to select against resistant bacteria using an approach termed collateral sensitivity cycling, which has recently been found to be relevant in developing treatment strategies for chronic infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Despite its promise, large-scale clinical and experimental studies revealed limited evidence of susceptibility to antibiotic cycling across various pathogens.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Another concern is that practitioners may become reluctant to perform routine surgeries because of the increased risk of harmful infection.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Backup treatments can have serious side-effects; for example, antibiotics like aminoglycosides (such as amikacin, gentamicin, kanamycin, streptomycin, etc.) used for the treatment of drug-resistant tuberculosis and cystic fibrosis can cause respiratory disorders, deafness and kidney failure.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The potential crisis at hand is the result of a marked decrease in industry research and development.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Poor financial investment in antibiotic research has exacerbated the situation.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In 2011, Pfizer, one of the last major pharmaceutical companies developing new antibiotics, shut down its primary research effort, citing poor shareholder returns relative to drugs for chronic illnesses.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] However, small and medium-sized pharmaceutical companies are still active in antibiotic drug research.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In particular, apart from classical synthetic chemistry methodologies, researchers have developed a combinatorial synthetic biology platform on single cell level in a high-throughput screening manner to diversify novel lanthipeptides.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In the 5–10 years since 2010, there has been a change in the ways new antimicrobial agents are discovered and developed – principally via the formation of public-private funding initiatives.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Later stage clinical development is supported by the AMR Action Fund, which in turn is supported by multiple investors with the aim of developing 2–4 new antimicrobial agents by 2030.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The discovery and development of new antimicrobial agents has been facilitated by regulatory advances, which have been principally led by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] These processes are increasingly aligned although important differences remain and drug developers must prepare separate documents.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] New development pathways have been developed to help with the approval of new antimicrobial agents that address unmet needs such as the Limited Population Pathway for Antibacterial and Antifungal Drugs (LPAD).
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] These new pathways are required because of difficulties in conducting large definitive phase III clinical trials in a timely way.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Some of the economic impediments to the development of new antimicrobial agents have been addressed by reimbursement schemes that delink payment of antimicrobials from volume-based sales.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The available classes of antifungal drugs are still limited but as of 2021 novel classes of antifungals are being developed and are undergoing various stages of clinical trials to assess performance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Scientists have started using advanced computational approaches with supercomputers for the development of new antibiotic derivatives to deal with antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Using antibiotic-free alternatives in bone infection treatment may help decrease the use of antibiotics and thus antimicrobial resistance.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The bone regeneration material bioactive glass S53P4 has shown to effectively inhibit the bacterial growth of up to 50 clinically relevant bacteria including MRSA and MRSE.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] During the last decades, copper and silver nanomaterials have demonstrated appealing features for the development of a new family of antimicrobial agents.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Nanoparticles (1–100 nm) show unique properties and promise as antimicrobial agents against resistant bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Silver (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) are extensively studied, disrupting bacterial cell membranes and interfering with protein synthesis.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Zinc oxide (ZnO NPs), copper (CuNPs), and silica (SiNPs) nanoparticles also exhibit antimicrobial properties.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] However, high synthesis costs, potential toxicity, and instability pose challenges.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] To overcome these, biological synthesis methods and combination therapies with other antimicrobials are explored.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Similar to the situation in malaria therapy, where successful treatments based on ancient recipes have been found, there has already been some success in finding and testing ancient drugs and other treatments that are effective against AMR bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] One of the key tools identified by the WHO and others for the fight against rising antimicrobial resistance is improved surveillance of the spread and movement of AMR genes through different communities and regions.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Recent advances in high-throughput DNA sequencing as a result of the Human Genome Project have resulted in the ability to determine the individual microbial genes in a sample.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Along with the availability of databases of known antimicrobial resistance genes, such as the Comprehensive Antimicrobial Resistance Database (CARD) and ResFinder, this allows the identification of all the antimicrobial resistance genes within the sample – the so-called "resistome".
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In doing so, a profile of these genes within a community or environment can be determined, providing information into how antimicrobial resistance is spreading through a population and allowing for the identification of resistance that is of concern.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phage therapy is the therapeutic use of bacteriophages to treat pathogenic bacterial infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phage therapy has many potential applications in human medicine as well as dentistry, veterinary science, and agriculture.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phage therapy relies on the use of naturally occurring bacteriophages to infect and lyse bacteria at the site of infection in a host.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Due to current advances in genetics and biotechnology these bacteriophages can possibly be manufactured to treat specific infections.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phages can be bioengineered to target multidrug-resistant bacterial infections, and their use involves the added benefit of preventing the elimination of beneficial bacteria in the human body.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Phages destroy bacterial cell walls and membrane through the use of lytic proteins which kill bacteria by making many holes from the inside out.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bacteriophages can even possess the ability to digest the biofilm that many bacteria develop that protect them from antibiotics to effectively infect and kill bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bioengineering can play a role in creating successful bacteriophages.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Understanding the mutual interactions and evolutions of bacterial and phage populations in the environment of a human or animal body is essential for rational phage therapy.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bacteriophagics are used against antibiotic resistant bacteria in Georgia (George Eliava Institute) and in one institute in Wrocław, Poland.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Bacteriophage cocktails are common drugs sold over the counter in pharmacies in eastern countries.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] In Belgium, four patients with severe musculoskeletal infections received bacteriophage therapy with concomitant antibiotics.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] After a single course of phage therapy, no recurrence of infection occurred and no severe side-effects related to the therapy were detected.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Analysing AMR data at scale requires dedicated computational approaches, as routine microbiological data from clinical laboratories can be large, heterogeneous, and subject to varying local standards.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] Several open-source tools have been developed to support this work.
[src:replica-plating/antibiotic-resistance-p03] The AMR package for R provides functions for standardising and analysing phenotypical resistance data, including interpretation of MIC and disk diffusion results against EUCAST and CLSI breakpoints, and calculation of resistance rates across patient populations.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Prototrophic cells are self-sufficient producers of all required metabolites (e.g. amino acids, lipids, cofactors), while auxotrophs require to be on medium with the metabolite that they cannot produce.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] For example, a methionine auxotrophic cell could only grow on a medium that contained methionine; otherwise, it would starve.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] In this example, this is because it is unable to produce its own methionine.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] However, a methionine prototrophic cell would be able to function and replicate on a medium with or without methionine.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Replica plating is a technique that transfers colonies from one plate to another in the same spot as the last plate so the different media plates can be compared side by side.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] It is used to compare the growth of the same colonies on different plates of media to determine which environments the bacterial colony can or cannot grow in (this gives insight to possible auxotrophic characteristics).
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The method of replica plating implemented by Joshua Lederberg and Esther Lederberg included auxotrophs that were temperature-sensitive; that is, their ability to synthesize was temperature-dependent.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] (Auxotrophs are usually not temperature-dependent.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] They can also depend on other factors.) It is also possible that an organism is auxotrophic to more than just one organic compound that it requires for growth.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] In genetics, a strain is said to be auxotrophic if it carries a mutation that renders it unable to synthesize an essential compound.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] For example, a yeast mutant with an inactivated uracil synthesis pathway gene is a uracil auxotroph (e.g., if the yeast orotidine 5'-phosphate decarboxylase gene is inactivated, the resultant strain is a uracil auxotroph).
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Such a strain is unable to synthesize uracil and will only be able to grow if uracil can be taken up from the environment.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] This is the opposite of a uracil prototroph, or in this case a wild-type strain, which can still grow in the absence of uracil.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Auxotrophic genetic markers are often used in molecular genetics; they were famously used in Beadle and Tatum's Nobel Prize-winning work on the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis, connecting mutations of genes to protein mutations.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] This then allows for biosynthetic or biochemical pathway mapping that can help determine which enzyme or enzymes are mutated and dysfunctional in the auxotrophic strains of bacteria being studied.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Researchers have used strains of *E. coli* auxotrophic for specific amino acids to introduce non-natural amino acid analogues into proteins.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] For instance cells auxotrophic for the amino acid phenylalanine can be grown in media supplemented with an analogue such as para-azido phenylalanine.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Many living things, including humans, are auxotrophic for large classes of compounds required for growth and must obtain these compounds through diet (see vitamin, essential nutrient, essential amino acid, essential fatty acid).
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The complex pattern of evolution of vitamin auxotrophy across the eukaryotic tree of life is intimately connected with the interdependence between organisms.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The Salmonella Mutagenesis test (Ames test) uses multiple strains of *Salmonella typhimurium* that are auxotrophic to histidine to test whether a given chemical can cause mutations by observing its auxotrophic property in response to an added chemical compound.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The mutation a chemical substance or compound causes is measured by applying it to the bacteria on a plate containing histidine then moving the bacteria to a new plate without sufficient histidine for continual growth.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] If the substance does not mutate the genome of the bacteria from auxotrophic to histidine back to prototrophic to histidine, then the bacteria would not show growth on the new plate.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] So by comparing the ratio of the bacteria on the new plate to the old plate and the same ratio for the control group, it is possible to quantify how mutagenic a substance is, or rather, how likely it is to cause mutations in DNA.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] A chemical is considered positive for Ames test if it causes mutations increasing the observed reversion rate and negative if presents similar to the control group.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] There is a normal, but small, number of revertant colonies expected when an auxotrophic bacteria is plated on a media without the metabolite it needs because it could mutate back to prototrophy.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The chances of this are low and therefore cause very small colonies to be formed.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] If a mutagenic substance is added, however, the number of revertants would be visibly higher than without the mutagenic substance.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The Ames test, basically, is considered positive if a substance increases chance of mutation in the DNA of the bacteria enough to cause a quantifiable difference in the revertants of the mutagen plate and the control group plate.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Negative Ames test means the possible mutagen DID not cause increase in revertants and positive Ames test signifies that the possible mutagen DID increase the chance of mutation.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] These mutagenic effects on bacteria are researched as a possible indicator of the same effects on larger organisms, like humans.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] It is suggested that if a mutation can arise in bacterial DNA under presence of a mutagen then the same effect would occur for larger organisms causing cancer.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] A negative Ames test result could suggest that the substance is not a mutagen and would not cause tumor formation in living organisms.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] However only few of the positive Ames Test resulting chemicals were considered insignificant when tested in larger organisms but the positive Ames test for bacteria still could not be conclusively linked to expression of cancer in larger organisms.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] While it can be a possible determinant of tumors for living organisms, humans, animals, and so on, more studies must be completed to come to a conclusion.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] A large number of unnatural amino acids, which are similar to their canonical counterparts in shape, size and chemical properties, are introduced into the recombinant proteins by means of auxotrophic expression hosts.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] For example, methionine (Met) or tryptophan (Trp) auxotrophic *Escherichia coli* strains can be cultivated in a defined minimal medium.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] In this experimental setup it is possible to express recombinant proteins whose canonical Trp and Met residues are completely substituted with different medium-supplemented related analogs.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] This methodology leads to a new form of protein engineering, which is not performed by codon manipulation at the DNA level (e.g. oligonucleotide-directed mutagenesis), but by codon reassignments at the level of protein translation under efficient selective pressure.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] Therefore, the method is referred as selective pressure incorporation (SPI).
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] No organism studied so far encodes other amino acids than the canonical twenty; two additional canonical amino acids (selenocysteine, pyrrolysine) are inserted into proteins by recoding translation termination signals.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] This boundary can be crossed by adaptive laboratory evolution of metabolically stable auxotrophic microbial strains.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] For example, the first clearly successful attempt to evolve *Escherichia coli* that can survive solely on the unnatural amino acid thieno[3,2-b]pyrrolyl) alanine as the only substitute for tryptophan was made in 2015.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] The 1993 film *Jurassic Park* (based on the 1990 Michael Crichton novel of the same name) features dinosaurs that were genetically altered so that they could not produce the amino acid lysine.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] This was known as the "lysine contingency" and was supposed to prevent the cloned dinosaurs from surviving outside the park, forcing them to be dependent on lysine supplements provided by the park's veterinary staff.
[src:replica-plating/auxotrophy] In reality, no animals are capable of producing lysine (it is an essential amino acid).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:replica-plating/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
